y:Ypres|Battle of Passchendaele]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c7:8d93:fe01:995:214e:844f:7ad5", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Passchendaele"}
{"title_page": "Guard Hussar Regiment (Denmark)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name          = Guard Hussar Regiment\n| native_name        = Gardehusarregimentet\n| image              = Emblem for the Danish Guard Hussar Regiment.svg\n| image_size         = 150px\n| alt                =\n| caption            = [[Cap badge]] of the Guard Hussars\n| dates              = {{nowrap| 17 November 1614&nbsp;\u2013 present<br />({{Age in years and months|1614|11|17}})}}\n| disbanded          =\n| country            = {{flag|Kingdom of Denmark}}\n| countries          =\n| allegiance         =\n| branch             = {{flagicon|Kingdom of Denmark}} [[Royal Danish Army]]\n| type               = [[Cavalry]]\n| role               = Armoured Infantry<br>Reconnaissance\n| size               = Five battalions\n| command_structure  = [[Army Staff (Denmark)|Army Staff]]\n| garrison           = I., II., IV & V Battalion \u2013 [[Antvorskov barracks]]<br>III.Battalion \u2013 [[Bornholm]]\n| garrison_label     =\n| nickname           = GHR\n| patron             =\n| motto              = ''In Actis Esto Volucris'' (Be swift in action)\n| colours            = [[File:Stable belt GHR.png|Stable belt GHR|80px]]<br /><br />[[File:Stable belt SPESK.PNG|80px]] (Used by III. Bataljon at Bornholm )\n| colours_label      = [[Stable belt|Regimental belt]]\n| march              = Garderhusarregimentets Signalmarch {{audio|Garderhusarregimentets Signal March.ogg|Play}}\n| mascot             =\n| anniversaries      = 17 November 1614<br> 10 February 1762\n| equipment          =\n| equipment_label    =\n| battles            = [[Thirty Years War]]<br>[[Torstenson War]]<br>[[Second Northern War|Second Nordic War]]<br>[[Scanian War]]<br>[[Nine Years' War]]<br>[[War of the Spanish Succession]]<br>[[Great Northern War|Great Nordic War]]<br>[[Napoleonic Wars]]<br>[[First Schleswig War]]<br>[[Second Schleswig War]]<br>[[German invasion of Denmark (1940)|Operation Weser\u00fcbung]]<br> [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]] <br> [[Iraq conflict (2003\u2013present)]]\n| decorations        =\n| battle_honours     =\n| battle_honours_label =\n| flying_hours       =\n| website            = {{url|http://forsvaret.dk/ghr/Pages/default.aspx|Official website}}\n<!-- Commanders -->\n| current_commander  = [[Colonel]] Jens Ole Rossen-J\u00f8rgensen\n| commander1         =\n| commander1_label   =\n| commander2         =\n| commander2_label   =\n| notable_commanders = Peder Aalborg<br>Caspar Hermann Gottlieb [[Moltke]]\n| ceremonial_chief   = [[Margrethe II of Denmark|HM The Queen of Denmark]]\n<!-- Insignia -->\n| identification_symbol         = [[File:GHR Colours.svg|150px]]\n| identification_symbol_label   = Colours\n| identification_symbol_2       = [[File:GHR estandart.svg|100px]]\n| identification_symbol_2_label = Standard\n| identification_symbol_3       = [[File:Coat of arms of the Danish Guard Hussar Regiment (former).svg|75px]]\n| identification_symbol_3_label = Former coat of arms\n}}\n\nThe '''Guard Hussar Regiment''' ({{lang-da|Gardehusarregimentet, GHR}}) is a special [[cavalry]] unit of the [[Royal Danish Army]], the primary task is to train the Guard Hussars for various functions in the mobilisation force.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Guard Hussars |url=http://www.visitsydvestsjaelland.dk/international/en-gb/menu/turist/oplevelser/attraktioner/garderhusarerne/gardehusar.htm |accessdate=July 25, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110513005919/http://www.visitsydvestsjaelland.dk/international/en-gb/menu/turist/oplevelser/attraktioner/garderhusarerne/gardehusar.htm |archivedate=May 13, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  The Guard Hussars are one of two active cavalry regiments of the [[Danish Army]], and was formed in 2001 through the amalgamation of the original Guard Hussars regiment, [[Sj\u00e6llandske Livregiment|Zealand Life Regiment]] and [[Danske Livregiment|Danish Life Regiment]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Regimentets historie |url=http://forsvaret.dk/GHR/Om%20GHR/Historisk/Pages/default.aspx |website=forsvaret.dk/GHR |publisher=Gardehusarregimentet |accessdate=28 September 2018 |language=Danish}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n=== Origins of the regiment===\n[[Image:GHR1.jpg|thumb|left|A Guard Hussar soldier interacts with the local population in [[Helmand, Afghanistan]].]]\nAlthough the Guard Hussars themselves date from [[1762 in Denmark|10 February 1762]], the Danish Army takes the date of the founding of a regiment from its oldest part, in this case the [[Zealand Life Regiment]], which was founded in 1614. This makes the Guard Hussars one of the oldest regiment of [[hussar]]s in the world still operational, it is also the only hussars in mounted parade uniform to still wear the slung and braided [[pelisse]] which was formerly characteristic of this class of cavalry. In addition to its operational role, the Guard Hussar Regiment is one of two regiments in the Danish Army (along with the [[Den Kongelige Livgarde]]) to be classed as 'Guards'; in this case, the [[Guard Hussar Regiment Mounted Squadron|Mounted Squadron]] perform the same role as the [[Household Cavalry]] do in the [[British Army]].\n\nFrom 1961 to 1972 the regiment was responsible for two armoured battalions, one recon battalion. From 1972\u20132000 the regiment was responsible for one armoured, one mechanised infantry, one reconnaissance and one infantry battalions. From 2000\u20132004 the regiment was responsible for two armoured, two mechanised infantry, one reconnaissance and two infantry battalions. From 1992\u20132004 the regiment also had to form two light Reconnaissance Squadrons assigned to the [[1st Zealand Brigade]] and [[Danish International Brigade]].\n\n=== 2001 amalgamation===\n\nAs part of the [[Danish Defence Agreement 2000\u201304|Defence Agreement 2000\u201304]], it was decided to merge the Guard Hussar Regiment with the [[Zealand Life Regiment]] and the [[Danish Life Regiment]]. With this amalgamation of the three infantry regiments; the name and history of the new regiment had to be decided. This led to what the media called \"the Colonels' War\" ({{lang-da|Oberstkrigen}}), with the three colonels fighting for their regiment's name and history to survive.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Br\u00f8ndum |first1=Christian |title=Dronningen fejrer tvivlsomt jubil\u00e6um |url=https://www.berlingske.dk/samfund/dronningen-fejrer-tvivlsomt-jubilaeum |website=b.dk |publisher=Berlingske Media |accessdate=28 September 2018 |language=Danish |date=17 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Br\u00f8ndum |first1=Christian |editor1-last=Bauneh\u00f8j |editor1-first=Birgit |title=Forsvaret g\u00e5r ikke med rygm\u00e6rker |journal=Forsvarsavisen |date=November 2016 |volume=5 |issue=8 |page=7 |url=https://www2.forsvaret.dk/omos/publikationer/forsvarsavisen/Documents/Forsvarsavisen%2008%202016%20small.pdf |accessdate=21 November 2018 |publisher=V\u00e6rnsf\u00e6lles Forsvarskommando}}</ref>\nThe Chief of Defence, [[Christian Hvidt]], ordered the old insignia removed, which was not customary. The new armoured horse head was nicknamed the \"[[Colors (motorcycling)|biker patch]]\". Furthermore, it was decided that a [[Military colours, standards and guidons|colour]] be used alongside the standard.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Br\u00f8ndum |first1=Christian |title=Gammelt nag ruster ikke |url=http://bevar.721.dk/htm/avisartikler.htm |publisher=Berlingske Tidende |accessdate=21 November 2018 |language=Danish |date=29 April 2002}}</ref>\n\n===Modern times===\nFollowing the amalgamation, the Guard Hussar Regiment has participated in a number of international missions, resulting in the loss of 16 soldiers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Danske milit\u00e6re tab i international tjeneste |url=http://www.fns-naestved.dk/Danske%20tab.htm |website=fns-naestved.dk |accessdate=1 October 2018 |language=Danish |date=31 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\nToday the Gardehusarregiment is classed as a cavalry regiment, it is in fact a mixed armoured and infantry unit, with three battalions:\n* [[File:GHR Shield 1.svg|25px]] '''1st Battalion''' \u2013 Armoured Infantry (part of 1st Brigade)\n** [[File:Emblem for the GHR 1Staff.svg|25px]] Staff Company\n** [[File:Emblem for the 1-I-GHR.svg|25px]] 1st Armoured Infantry Company (1/I/GHR)\n** [[File:Emblem for the 2-I-GHR.svg|25px]] 2nd Mechanised Infantry Company (2/I/GHR)\n* [[File:GHR Shield 3.svg|25px]] '''3rd Battalion''' \u2013 Reconnaissance (part of 2nd Brigade) '''motto''':''Nec temere nec timide'' (Neither random nor timidly)\n** [[File:Emblem for the GHR 3Staff.svg|25px]] Staff Platoon (Inactive)\n** [[File:Emblem for the GHR 1 LOPKESK.svg|25px]] 1st Light Reconnaissance Squadron (1 LOPKESK)\n** [[File:Emblem for the GHR 2LOPKESK.svg|25px]] 2nd Light Reconnaissance Squadron (2 LOPKESK)\n** [[File:Emblem for the Danish 3rd Marine Squadron.svg|25px]] 3rd Basic Training Squadron (3 HBUESK)\n** [[File:Insigne incognitum.svg|25px]] ? Light Reconnaissance Squadron (inactive until 2021)\n* [[File:GHR Shield 5.svg|25px]] '''5th Battalion''' \u2013 Basic Training (part of 2nd Brigade)  '''motto''':''Terror in Hostes \u2013 Vor fjender til frygt''\n** [[File:Emblem for the 1-V-GHR.svg|25px]] 1st Basic Training Company '''motto''':''Fremad p\u00e5 ny \u2013 hurtig og adr\u00e6t'' (Forward again - fast and agile)\n** [[File:Emblem for the LIV-V-GHR.svg|25px]] 2nd Basic Training Company (Livkompagniet) '''motto''':''Fremad p\u00e5 ny \u2013 lige p\u00e5 og h\u00e5rdt'' (Forward again - head on)\n** [[File:Emblem for the 4-V-GHR.svg|25px]] 4th Mechanised Infantry Company (4/V/GHR)\n* [[File:HESK logo.svg|25px]] '''[[Guard Hussar Regiment Mounted Squadron|HESK]]''' \u2013 Public duties/ceremonial\n\n;Disband Units\n*  II/GHR (1955\u22121976) Armoured Battalion, (1977-2000) Infantry Battalion, (2001-2018) Armoured Infantry Battalion\n*  IV/GHR (1983\u22122000) Infantry Battalion, (2001-2013) Armoured Infantry Battalion.\n*  VI/GHR (2000-2004) Infantry Battalion. \n*  VII/GHR (2000-2004) Infantry Battalion.\n\n==Names of the regiment==\n{| class=\"toccolours\" \n|+ style=\"font-size: larger; margin-left: 1em;\"|'''Names<ref>{{cite web|last1=Laursen|first1=Ole|title=Historical Overview of Guard Hussar Regiment|url=http://www.wadschier.dk/haeren-garnisoner-regimentschefer/haer/garderhusarregimentet/19/|website=Wadschier|accessdate=5 June 2017|date=22 April 2014}}</ref>'''\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n|''Husarregimentet''||Hussar Regiment||width=\"12%\"| 1762-02-10 ||width=\"1%\"|\u2013||width=\"12%\"| 1780\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n|''1. og 2. Husaregiment''||1st and 2nd Hussar Regiment||width=\"12%\"| 1780 ||width=\"1%\"|\u2013||width=\"12%\"| 1785\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n|''1. og 2. Husarkorps''||1st and 2nd Hussar Corps||width=\"12%\"| 1785 ||width=\"1%\"|\u2013||width=\"12%\"| 1788\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n|''Husarregimentet''||Hussar Regiment||width=\"12%\"| 1788 ||width=\"1%\"|\u2013||width=\"12%\"| 1842\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n|''Garderhusardivisionen''||Guard Hussar Division||width=\"12%\"| 1842 ||width=\"1%\"|\u2013||width=\"12%\"| 1855 \n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n|''Husarregimentet''||Hussar Regiment||width=\"12%\"| 1855 ||width=\"1%\"|\u2013||width=\"12%\"| 1856\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n|''Gardehusarregimentet''||Guard Hussar Regiment ||width=\"12%\"| 1856 ||width=\"1%\"|\u2013||width=\"12%\"| Present\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=35em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{url|https://www.facebook.com/Gardehusarregimentet-419093551577062/|Official Facebook}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{Military of Denmark}}\n{{Regiments of Denmark}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 2001]]\n[[Category:Danish Army regiments]]\n[[Category:Guards regiments]]\n[[Category:Cavalry regiments of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Military of Denmark]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name          = Guard Hussar Regiment\n| native_name        = Gardehusarregimentet\n| image              = Emblem for the Danish Guard Hussar Regiment.svg\n| image_size         = 150px\n| alt                =\n| caption            = [[Cap badge]] of the Guard Hussars\n| dates              = {{nowrap| 17 November 1614&nbsp;\u2013 present<br />({{Age in years and months|1614|11|17}})}}\n| disbanded          =\n| country            = {{flag|Kingdom of Denmark}}\n| countries          =\n| allegiance         =\n| branch             = {{flagicon|Kingdom of Denmark}} [[Royal Danish Army]]\n| type               = [[Cavalry]]\n| role               = Armoured Infantry<br>Reconnaissance\n| size               = Five battalions\n| command_structure  = [[Army Staff (Denmark)|Army Staff]]\n| garrison           = I., II., IV & V Battalion \u2013 [[Antvorskov barracks]]<br>III.Battalion \u2013 [[Bornholm]]\n| garrison_label     =\n| nickname           = GHR\n| patron             =\n| motto              = ''In Actis Esto Volucris'' (Be swift in action)\n| colours            = [[File:Stable belt GHR.png|Stable belt GHR|80px]]<br /><br />[[File:Stable belt SPESK.PNG|80px]] (Used by III. Bataljon at Bornholm )\n| colours_label      = [[Stable belt|Regimental belt]]\n| march              = Garderhusarregimentets Signalmarch {{audio|Garderhusarregimentets Signal March.ogg|Play}}\n| mascot             =\n| anniversaries      = 17 November 1614<br> 10 February 1762\n| equipment          =\n| equipment_label    =\n| battles            = [[Thirty Years War]]<br>[[Torstenson War]]<br>[[Second Northern War|Second Nordic War]]<br>[[Scanian War]]<br>[[Nine Years' War]]<br>[[War of the Spanish Succession]]<br>[[Great Northern War|Great Nordic War]]<br>[[Napoleonic Wars]]<br>[[First Schleswig War]]<br>[[Second Schleswig War]]<br>[[German invasion of Denmark (1940)|Operation Weser\u00fcbung]]<br> [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]] <br> [[Iraq conflict (2003\u2013present)]]\n| decorations        =\n| battle_honours     =\n| battle_honours_label =\n| flying_hours       =\n| website            = {{url|http://forsvaret.dk/ghr/Pages/default.aspx|Official website}}\n<!-- Commanders -->\n| current_commander  = [[Colonel]] Jens Ole Rossen-J\u00f8rgensen\n| commander1         =\n| commander1_label   =\n| commander2         =\n| commander2_label   =\n| notable_commanders = Peder Aalborg<br>Caspar Hermann Gottlieb [[Moltke]]\n| ceremonial_chief   = [[Margrethe II of Denmark|HM The Queen of Denmark]]\n<!-- Insignia -->\n| identification_symbol         = [[File:GHR Colours.svg|150px]]\n| identification_symbol_label   = Colours\n| identification_symbol_2       = [[File:GHR estandart.svg|100px]]\n| identification_symbol_2_label = Standard\n| identification_symbol_3       = [[File:Coat of arms of the Danish Guard Hussar Regiment (former).svg|75px]]\n| identification_symbol_3_label = Former coat of arms\n}}\n\nThe '''Guard Hussar Regiment''' ({{lang-da|Gardehusarregimentet, GHR}}) is a special [[cavalry]] unit of the [[Royal Danish Army]], the primary task is to train the Guard Hussars for various functions in the mobilisation force.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Guard Hussars |url=http://www.visitsydvestsjaelland.dk/international/en-gb/menu/turist/oplevelser/attraktioner/garderhusarerne/gardehusar.htm |accessdate=July 25, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110513005919/http://www.visitsydvestsjaelland.dk/international/en-gb/menu/turist/oplevelser/attraktioner/garderhusarerne/gardehusar.htm |archivedate=May 13, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  The Guard Hussars are one of two active cavalry regiments of the [[Danish Army]], and was formed in 2001 through the amalgamation of the original Guard Hussars regiment, [[Sj\u00e6llandske Livregiment|Zealand Life Regiment]] and [[Danske Livregiment|Danish Life Regiment]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Regimentets historie |url=http://forsvaret.dk/GHR/Om%20GHR/Historisk/Pages/default.aspx |website=forsvaret.dk/GHR |publisher=Gardehusarregimentet |accessdate=28 September 2018 |language=Danish}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n=== Origins of the regiment===\n[[Image:GHR1.jpg|thumb|left|A Guard Hussar soldier interacts with the local population in [[Helmand, Afghanistan]].]]\nAlthough the Guard Hussars themselves date from [[1762 in Denmark|10 February 1762]], the Danish Army takes the date of the founding of a regiment from its oldest part, in this case the [[Zealand Life Regiment]], which was founded in 1614. This makes the Guard Hussars one of the oldest regiment of [[hussar]]s in the world still operational, it is also the only hussars in mounted parade uniform to still wear the slung and braided [[pelisse]] which was formerly characteristic of this class of cavalry. In addition to its operational role, the Guard Hussar Regiment is one of two regiments in the Danish Army (along with the [[Den Kongelige Livgarde]]) to be classed as 'Guards'; in this case, the [[Guard Hussar Regiment Mounted Squadron|Mounted Squadron]] perform the same role as the [[Household Cavalry]] do in the [[British Army]].\n\nFrom 1961 to 1972 the regiment was responsible for two armoured battalions, one recon battalion. From 1972\u20132000 the regiment was responsible for one armoured, one mechanised infantry, one reconnaissance and one infantry battalions. From 2000\u20132004 the regiment was responsible for two armoured, two mechanised infantry, one reconnaissance and two infantry battalions. From 1992\u20132004 the regiment also had to form two light Reconnaissance Squadrons assigned to the [[1st Zealand Brigade]] and [[Danish International Brigade]].\n\n=== 2001 amalgamation===\n\nAs part of the [[Danish Defence Agreement 2000\u201304|Defence Agreement 2000\u201304]], it was decided to merge the Guard Hussar Regiment with the [[Zealand Life Regiment]] and the [[Danish Life Regiment]]. With this amalgamation of the three infantry regiments; the name and history of the new regiment had to be decided. This led to what the media called \"the Colonels' War\" ({{lang-da|Oberstkrigen}}), with the three colonels fighting for their regiment's name and history to survive.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Br\u00f8ndum |first1=Christian |title=Dronningen fejrer tvivlsomt jubil\u00e6um |url=https://www.berlingske.dk/samfund/dronningen-fejrer-tvivlsomt-jubilaeum |website=b.dk |publisher=Berlingske Media |accessdate=28 September 2018 |language=Danish |date=17 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Br\u00f8ndum |first1=Christian |editor1-last=Bauneh\u00f8j |editor1-first=Birgit |title=Forsvaret g\u00e5r ikke med rygm\u00e6rker |journal=Forsvarsavisen |date=November 2016 |volume=5 |issue=8 |page=7 |url=https://www2.forsvaret.dk/omos/publikationer/forsvarsavisen/Documents/Forsvarsavisen%2008%202016%20small.pdf |accessdate=21 November 2018 |publisher=V\u00e6rnsf\u00e6lles Forsvarskommando}}</ref>\nThe Chief of Defence, [[Christian Hvidt]], ordered the old insignia removed, which was not customary. The new armoured horse head was nicknamed the \"[[Colors (motorcycling)|biker patch]]\". Furthermore, it was decided that a [[Military colours, standards and guidons|colour]] be used alongside the standard.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Br\u00f8ndum |first1=Christian |title=Gammelt nag ruster ikke |url=http://bevar.721.dk/htm/avisartikler.htm |publisher=Berlingske Tidende |accessdate=21 November 2018 |language=Danish |date=29 April 2002}}</ref>\n\n===Modern times===\nFollowing the amalgamation, the Guard Hussar Regiment has participated in a number of international missions, resulting in the loss of 16 soldiers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Danske milit\u00e6re tab i international tjeneste |url=http://www.fns-naestved.dk/Danske%20tab.htm |website=fns-naestved.dk |accessdate=1 October 2018 |language=Danish |date=31 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\nToday the Gardehusarregiment is classed as a cavalry regiment, it is in fact a mixed armoured and infantry unit, with three battalions:\n* [[File:GHR Shield 1.svg|25px]] '''1st Battalion''' \u2013 Armoured Infantry (part of 1st Brigade)\n** [[File:Emblem for the GHR 1Staff.svg|25px]] Staff Company\n** [[File:Emblem for the 1-I-GHR.svg|25px]] 1st Armoured Infantry Company (1/I/GHR)\n** [[File:Emblem for the 2-I-GHR.svg|25px]] 2nd Mechanised Infantry Company (2/I/GHR)\n* [[File:GHR Shield 3.svg|25px]] '''3rd Battalion''' \u2013 Reconnaissance (part of 2nd Brigade) '''motto''':''Nec temere nec timide'' (Neither random nor timidly)\n** [[File:Emblem for the GHR 3Staff.svg|25px]] Staff Platoon (Inactive)\n** [[File:Emblem for the GHR 1 LOPKESK.svg|25px]] 1st Light Reconnaissance Squadron (1 LOPKESK)\n** [[File:Emblem for the GHR 2LOPKESK.svg|25px]] 2nd Light Reconnaissance Squadron (2 LOPKESK)\n** [[File:Insigne incognitum.svg|25px]] ? Light Reconnaissance Squadron (inactive until 2021)\n** [[File:Emblem for the Danish 3rd Marine Squadron.svg|25px]] 3rd Basic Training Squadron (3 HBUESK)\n* [[File:GHR Shield 5.svg|25px]] '''5th Battalion''' \u2013 Basic Training (part of 2nd Brigade)  '''motto''':''Terror in Hostes \u2013 Vor fjender til frygt''\n** [[File:Emblem for the 1-V-GHR.svg|25px]] 1st Basic Training Company '''motto''':''Fremad p\u00e5 ny \u2013 hurtig og adr\u00e6t'' (Forward again - fast and agile)\n** [[File:Emblem for the LIV-V-GHR.svg|25px]] 2nd Basic Training Company (Livkompagniet) '''motto''':''Fremad p\u00e5 ny \u2013 lige p\u00e5 og h\u00e5rdt'' (Forward again - head on)\n** [[File:Emblem for the 4-V-GHR.svg|25px]] 4th Mechanised Infantry Company (4/V/GHR)\n* [[File:HESK logo.svg|25px]] '''[[Guard Hussar Regiment Mounted Squadron|HESK]]''' \u2013 Public duties/ceremonial\n\n;Disband Units\n*  II/GHR (1955\u22121976) Armoured Battalion, (1977-2000) Infantry Battalion, (2001-2018) Armoured Infantry Battalion\n*  IV/GHR (1983\u22122000) Infantry Battalion, (2001-2013) Armoured Infantry Battalion.\n*  VI/GHR (2000-2004) Infantry Battalion. \n*  VII/GHR (2000-2004) Infantry Battalion.\n\n==Names of the regiment==\n{| class=\"toccolours\" \n|+ style=\"font-size: larger; margin-left: 1em;\"|'''Names<ref>{{cite web|last1=Laursen|first1=Ole|title=Historical Overview of Guard Hussar Regiment|url=http://www.wadschier.dk/haeren-garnisoner-regimentschefer/haer/garderhusarregimentet/19/|website=Wadschier|accessdate=5 June 2017|date=22 April 2014}}</ref>'''\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n|''Husarregimentet''||Hussar Regiment||width=\"12%\"| 1762-02-10 ||width=\"1%\"|\u2013||width=\"12%\"| 1780\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n|''1. og 2. Husaregiment''||1st and 2nd Hussar Regiment||width=\"12%\"| 1780 ||width=\"1%\"|\u2013||width=\"12%\"| 1785\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n|''1. og 2. Husarkorps''||1st and 2nd Hussar Corps||width=\"12%\"| 1785 ||width=\"1%\"|\u2013||width=\"12%\"| 1788\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n|''Husarregimentet''||Hussar Regiment||width=\"12%\"| 1788 ||width=\"1%\"|\u2013||width=\"12%\"| 1842\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n|''Garderhusardivisionen''||Guard Hussar Division||width=\"12%\"| 1842 ||width=\"1%\"|\u2013||width=\"12%\"| 1855 \n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n|''Husarregimentet''||Hussar Regiment||width=\"12%\"| 1855 ||width=\"1%\"|\u2013||width=\"12%\"| 1856\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n|''Gardehusarregimentet''||Guard Hussar Regiment ||width=\"12%\"| 1856 ||width=\"1%\"|\u2013||width=\"12%\"| Present\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=35em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{url|https://www.facebook.com/Gardehusarregimentet-419093551577062/|Official Facebook}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{Military of Denmark}}\n{{Regiments of Denmark}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 2001]]\n[[Category:Danish Army regiments]]\n[[Category:Guards regiments]]\n[[Category:Cavalry regiments of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Military of Denmark]]\n", "name_user": "Skjoldbro", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStructure", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guard_Hussar_Regiment_(Denmark)"}
{"title_page": "Energy flow (ecology)", "text_new": "{{other uses|Energy flow (disambiguation)}}\n{{Refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n\n<div class=\"thumb tright\" style=\"background:#f9f9f9; border:1px solid #ccc; margin:0.5em;\">\n[[File:EnergyFlowFrog.jpg|200px]][[File:EnergyFlowTransformity.jpg|200px]]\n<div style=\"border: none; width:375px;\"><div class=\"thumbcaption\">'''Left:''' Energy flow diagram of a frog. The frog represents a node in an extended food web. The energy ingested is utilized for metabolic processes and transformed into biomass. The energy flow continues on its path if the frog is ingested by predators, parasites, or as a decaying [[Carrion|carcass]] in soil. This energy flow diagram illustrates how energy is lost as it fuels the metabolic process that transform the energy and nutrients into biomass.<br> '''Right:''' An expanded three link energy food chain (1. plants, 2. herbivores, 3. carnivores) illustrating the relationship between food flow diagrams and energy transformity. The transformity of energy becomes degraded, dispersed, and diminished from higher quality to lesser quantity as the energy within a food chain flows from one trophic species into another The study of the flow of energy within an ecological system from the time the energy enters the living system until it is ultimately degraded to heat and irretrievably lost from the system. It is also referred to as production ecology, because ecologists use the word production to describe the process of energy input and storage in ecosystems. Abbreviations: I=input, A=assimilation, R=respiration, NU=not utilized, P=production, B=biomass.<ref name=\"Odum88\">{{cite journal | last1=Odum | first1=H. T. | year=1988 | title=Self-organization, transformity, and information | journal=Science | volume=242 | issue=4882 | pages=1132\u20131139 | jstor=1702630 | doi=10.1126/science.242.4882.1132 | pmid=17799729| bibcode=1988Sci...242.1132O }}</ref>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\nIn [[ecology]], '''energy flow''', also called the '''calorific flow''', refers to the flow of [[energy]] through a [[food chain]], and is the focus of study in '''ecological energetics'''. In an [[ecosystem]], [[ecologist]]s seek to [[Quantification (science)|quantify]] the relative importance of different component [[species]] and feeding relationships.\n== History of ecological energetics == Ecological energetics appears to have grown out of the [[Age of Enlightenment]] and the concerns of the [[Physiocrats]]. It began in the works of [[Sergei Podolinsky]] in the late 1800s, and subsequently was developed by the Soviet ecologist [[Vladmir Stanchinsky]], the Austro-American [[Alfred J. Lotka]], and American limnologists, [[Raymond Lindeman]] and [[G. Evelyn Hutchinson]]. It underwent substantial development by [[Howard T. Odum]] and was applied by [[systems ecology|systems ecologists]], and [[radiation ecology|radiation ecologists]].\nA general energy flow scenario follows:\n*[[Solar energy]] is fixed by the [[photoautotroph]]s, called primary producers, like green [[plant]]s. [[Primary consumers]] absorb most of the stored energy in the plant through [[digestion]], and transform it into the form of energy they need, such as [[adenosine triphosphate]] (ATP), through [[cellular respiration|respiration]]. A part of the energy received by primary consumers, [[herbivore]]s, is converted to [[thermoregulation|body heat]] (an effect of respiration), which is [[radiant energy|radiated]] away and lost from the system. The loss of energy through body heat is far greater in [[warm-blooded]] animals, which must eat much more frequently than those that are [[Ectotherm|cold-blooded]]. Energy loss also occurs in the expulsion of [[digestion|undigested]] food (egesta) by [[excrement|excretion]] or [[regurgitation (digestion)|regurgitation]].\n*Secondary consumers, [[carnivore]]s, then consume the primary consumers, although [[omnivore]]s also consume primary producers. Energy that had been used by the primary consumers for growth and storage is thus absorbed into the secondary consumers through the process of digestion. As with primary consumers, secondary consumers convert this energy into a more suitable form (ATP) during respiration. Again, some energy is lost from the system, since energy which the primary consumers had used for respiration and regulation of body temperature cannot be utilized by the secondary consumers.\n*Tertiary consumers, which may or may not be [[apex predator]]s, then consume the secondary consumers, with some energy passed on and some lost, as with the lower levels of the food chain.\n*A final link in the food chain are [[decomposer]]s which break down the [[organic matter]] of the tertiary consumers (or whichever consumer is at the top of the chain) and release [[nutrient]]s into the [[soil]]. They also break down plants, herbivores and carnivores that were not eaten by organisms higher on the food chain, as well as the undigested food that is excreted by herbivores and carnivores. [[Saprotrophic nutrition|Saprotrophic]] [[bacteria]] and [[fungi]] are decomposers, and play a pivotal role in the [[nitrogen cycle|nitrogen]] and [[carbon cycle]]s.\n\nThe energy is passed on from [[trophic level]] to trophic level and each time about 90% of the energy is lost, with some being lost as heat into the environment (an effect of [[respiration (physiology)|respiration]]) and some being lost as incompletely digested food (egesta). Therefore, primary consumers get about 10% of the energy produced by autotrophs, while secondary consumers get 1% and tertiary consumers get 0.1%. This means the top consumer of a [[food chain]] receives the least energy, as a lot of the food chain's energy has been lost between trophic levels. This loss of energy at each level limits typical food chains to only four to six links.\n\n== History of ecological energetics ==\nEcological energetics appears to have grown out of the [[Age of Enlightenment]] and the concerns of the [[Physiocrats]]. It began in the works of [[Sergei Podolinsky]] in the late 1800s, and subsequently was developed by the Soviet ecologist [[Vladmir Stanchinsky]], the Austro-American [[Alfred J. Lotka]], and American limnologists, [[Raymond Lindeman]] and [[G. Evelyn Hutchinson]]. It underwent substantial development by [[Howard T. Odum]] and was applied by [[systems ecology|systems ecologists]], and [[radiation ecology|radiation ecologists]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ecological stoichiometry]]\n* [[Energy]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal|author=S. Podolinsky|year=2004|title=Socialism and the Unity of Physical Forces|journal=[[Organization & Environment]]|volume=17|issue=1|pp=61\u201375|doi=10.1177/1086026603262092}}\n* {{cite book|author=D.R. Weiner|year=2000|title=Models of Nature: Ecology, Conservation and Cultural Revolution in Soviet Russia|publisher=[[University of Pittsburgh Press]]|location=U.S.}}\n\n{{modelling ecosystems|state=expanded}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Energy Flow}}\n[[Category:Ecology terminology]]\n[[Category:Energy]]\n[[Category:Environmental science]]\n[[Category:Ecological economics]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|Energy flow (disambiguation)}}\n{{Refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n\n<div class=\"thumb tright\" style=\"background:#f9f9f9; border:1px solid #ccc; margin:0.5em;\">\n[[File:EnergyFlowFrog.jpg|200px]][[File:EnergyFlowTransformity.jpg|200px]]\n<div style=\"border: none; width:375px;\"><div class=\"thumbcaption\">'''Left:''' Energy flow diagram of a frog. The frog represents a node in an extended food web. The energy ingested is utilized for metabolic processes and transformed into biomass. The energy flow continues on its path if the frog is ingested by predators, parasites, or as a decaying [[Carrion|carcass]] in soil. This energy flow diagram illustrates how energy is lost as it fuels the metabolic process that transform the energy and nutrients into biomass.<br> '''Right:''' An expanded three link energy food chain (1. plants, 2. herbivores, 3. carnivores) illustrating the relationship between food flow diagrams and energy transformity. The transformity of energy becomes degraded, dispersed, and diminished from higher quality to lesser quantity as the energy within a food chain flows from one trophic species into another The study of the flow of energy within an ecological system from the time the energy enters the living system until it is ultimately degraded to heat and irretrievably lost from the system. It is also referred to as production ecology, because ecologists use the word production to describe the process of energy input and storage in ecosystems. Abbreviations: I=input, A=assimilation, R=respiration, NU=not utilized, P=production, B=biomass.<ref name=\"Odum88\">{{cite journal | last1=Odum | first1=H. T. | year=1988 | title=Self-organization, transformity, and information | journal=Science | volume=242 | issue=4882 | pages=1132\u20131139 | jstor=1702630 | doi=10.1126/science.242.4882.1132 | pmid=17799729| bibcode=1988Sci...242.1132O }}</ref>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\nIn [[ecology]], '''energy flow''', also called the '''calorific flow''', refers to the flow of [[energy]] through a [[food chain]], and is the focus of study in '''ecological energetics'''. In an [[ecosystem]], [[ecologist]]s seek to [[Quantification (science)|quantify]] the relative importance of different component [[species]] and feeding relationships.\n\nA general energy flow scenario follows:\n*[[Solar energy]] is fixed by the [[photoautotroph]]s, called primary producers, like green [[plant]]s. [[Primary consumers]] absorb most of the stored energy in the plant through [[digestion]], and transform it into the form of energy they need, such as [[adenosine triphosphate]] (ATP), through [[cellular respiration|respiration]]. A part of the energy received by primary consumers, [[herbivore]]s, is converted to [[thermoregulation|body heat]] (an effect of respiration), which is [[radiant energy|radiated]] away and lost from the system. The loss of energy through body heat is far greater in [[warm-blooded]] animals, which must eat much more frequently than those that are [[Ectotherm|cold-blooded]]. Energy loss also occurs in the expulsion of [[digestion|undigested]] food (egesta) by [[excrement|excretion]] or [[regurgitation (digestion)|regurgitation]].\n*Secondary consumers, [[carnivore]]s, then consume the primary consumers, although [[omnivore]]s also consume primary producers. Energy that had been used by the primary consumers for growth and storage is thus absorbed into the secondary consumers through the process of digestion. As with primary consumers, secondary consumers convert this energy into a more suitable form (ATP) during respiration. Again, some energy is lost from the system, since energy which the primary consumers had used for respiration and regulation of body temperature cannot be utilized by the secondary consumers.\n*Tertiary consumers, which may or may not be [[apex predator]]s, then consume the secondary consumers, with some energy passed on and some lost, as with the lower levels of the food chain.\n*A final link in the food chain are [[decomposer]]s which break down the [[organic matter]] of the tertiary consumers (or whichever consumer is at the top of the chain) and release [[nutrient]]s into the [[soil]]. They also break down plants, herbivores and carnivores that were not eaten by organisms higher on the food chain, as well as the undigested food that is excreted by herbivores and carnivores. [[Saprotrophic nutrition|Saprotrophic]] [[bacteria]] and [[fungi]] are decomposers, and play a pivotal role in the [[nitrogen cycle|nitrogen]] and [[carbon cycle]]s.\n\nThe energy is passed on from [[trophic level]] to trophic level and each time about 90% of the energy is lost, with some being lost as heat into the environment (an effect of [[respiration (physiology)|respiration]]) and some being lost as incompletely digested food (egesta). Therefore, primary consumers get about 10% of the energy produced by autotrophs, while secondary consumers get 1% and tertiary consumers get 0.1%. This means the top consumer of a [[food chain]] receives the least energy, as a lot of the food chain's energy has been lost between trophic levels. This loss of energy at each level limits typical food chains to only four to six links.\n\n== History of ecological energetics ==\nEcological energetics appears to have grown out of the [[Age of Enlightenment]] and the concerns of the [[Physiocrats]]. It began in the works of [[Sergei Podolinsky]] in the late 1800s, and subsequently was developed by the Soviet ecologist [[Vladmir Stanchinsky]], the Austro-American [[Alfred J. Lotka]], and American limnologists, [[Raymond Lindeman]] and [[G. Evelyn Hutchinson]]. It underwent substantial development by [[Howard T. Odum]] and was applied by [[systems ecology|systems ecologists]], and [[radiation ecology|radiation ecologists]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ecological stoichiometry]]\n* [[Energy]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal|author=S. Podolinsky|year=2004|title=Socialism and the Unity of Physical Forces|journal=[[Organization & Environment]]|volume=17|issue=1|pp=61\u201375|doi=10.1177/1086026603262092}}\n* {{cite book|author=D.R. Weiner|year=2000|title=Models of Nature: Ecology, Conservation and Cultural Revolution in Soviet Russia|publisher=[[University of Pittsburgh Press]]|location=U.S.}}\n\n{{modelling ecosystems|state=expanded}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Energy Flow}}\n[[Category:Ecology terminology]]\n[[Category:Energy]]\n[[Category:Environmental science]]\n[[Category:Ecological economics]]\n", "name_user": "Yifan is a wu48", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Energy_flow_(ecology)"}
{"title_page": "International representation of Donetsk and Luhansk", "text_new": "{{POV|date=April 2020}} \n\nThe '''[[Donetsk People's Republic]]''' (DNR) and the '''[[Luhansk People's Republic]]''' (LNR) are two unrecognized [[proto-state]]s located in the [[Donbass]] region of eastern [[Ukraine]]. Internationally, they are recognized as constituent regions of Ukraine as the [[Donetsk Oblast|Donetsk]] and [[Luhansk Oblast|Luhansk]] oblasts, respectfully.<ref>[http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/world/2014-03/28/c_126325576.htm ''UN General Assembly adopts resolution affirming Ukraine's territorial integrity'', Xinhua 28 March 2014.]</ref> They proclaimed their independence after the [[2014 Ukrainian revolution]] and the subsequent [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|Russian military intervention]], later on merging together as the unrecognized state of [[Novorossiya]], only to be dissolved in 2015. Today, they are only oficially recognized by [[South Ossetia]]. Both entities have no embassies in any other state.\n\n==DNR Representation Bureaus==\n* {{CZE}} \u2013 in 2016, DNR sympathizers opened a self-proclaimed \"Consulate\" in [[Ostrava]]<ref>[http://www.rferl.org/a/ukraine-donetsk-czech-consulate-ostrava-liskova/27962142.html ''Donetsk Separatists Fly Flag At Czech Center That Prague Vows To Close'', RFE/RL 2. September 2016.]</ref><ref>[https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2016/09/02/donetsk-separatists-open-a-consulate-in-the-czech-republic-a55203 ''Donetsk Separatists Open 'Consulate' in the Czech Republic'', Moscow Times 2. September 2016.]</ref>\n* {{FRA}} \u2013 in 2017, a DNR Representative Office opened in [[Marseille]]<ref>[https://dnrsovet.su/vladislav-berdichevsky-dpr-representative-centre-in-france-will-help-europeans-learn-truth-about-civil-war-in-donbass/ ''Vladislav Berdichevsky: DPR Representative Centre in France will help Europeans learn truth about civil war in Donbass'', DNR Soviet 26. September 2017.]</ref>\n* {{ITA}} \