438 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u0432\u044b\u0434\u0430\u0447\u0438 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043f\u0430\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u0436\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044f\u043c \u041b\u041d\u0420'', Novaya Gazeta 29. April 2019.]</ref>\n* {{flagicon|South Ossetia}} [[South Ossetia]] \u2013 in 2015, a LNR Representative Office opened in [[Tskhinval]]<ref>[https://tass.com/world/792316 ''DPR and LPR opens representative office in South Ossetia'', TASS 28. April 2015.]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[International recognition of Donetsk and Luhansk]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Donetsk People's Republic]]\n[[Category:Luhansk People's Republic]]\n[[Category:Lists of diplomatic missions by sending country]]\n", "name_user": "Derim Hunt", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_representation_of_Donetsk_and_Luhansk"}
{"title_page": "Willamette Valley", "text_new": "{{short description|valley in the Pacific Northwest region of the United States}}\n{{About|the geographic feature}}\n{{Infobox valley\n| name            = Willamette Valley\n| other_name      = \n| photo           =  Wvatbethel1.jpg \n| photo_caption   = Farmscape in northern [[Polk County, Oregon|Polk County]]\n<!-- MAP -->\n| map_image       = Small-Oregon-Map.png\n| map_caption     = The Willamette Valley contains most of Oregon's population; it extends from Newberg in the north to Eugene in the south.\n| location        = [[United States]], [[Oregon]]\n| relief          = \n| label           = \n| label_position  = \n| coordinates     = {{coord}}\n| coordinates_ref = \n<!-- Statistics -->  \n| elevation       = \n| elevation_m     = \n| elevation_ft    = \n| elevation_ref   = \n| direction       = \n| length          = \n| width           = \n| area            = \n| depth           = \n| type            = \n| age             = \n| boundaries      = [[Cascade Range]] (East)<br>[[Oregon Coast Range]] (West)<br>[[Calapooya Mountains]] (South)\n| topo            = \n| towns           = \n| traversed       = \n| watercourses    = [[Willamette River]]\n<!-- Below --> \n| footnotes       = \n| embed           = \n}}\n[[File:Wpdms shdrlfi020l willamette valley.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Willamette Valley [[drainage basin|basin]]]]\nThe '''Willamette Valley''' ({{IPAc-en|w|\u1d7b|\u02c8|l|\u00e6|m|\u1d7b|t}}) is a {{convert|150|mi|km|adj=on}} long valley in [[Oregon]], in the [[Pacific Northwest]] region of the [[United States]]. The [[Willamette River]] flows the entire length of the valley, and it is surrounded by mountains on three sides \u2013 the [[Cascade Range]] to the east, the [[Oregon Coast Range]] to the west, and the [[Calapooya Mountains]] to the south. \n\nThe valley is synonymous with the cultural and political heart of Oregon, and is home to approximately 70&nbsp;percent of its population<ref>Loy, ''et al.'', p. 35</ref> including the six largest cities in the state: [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Eugene, Oregon|Eugene]], [[Salem, Oregon|Salem]], [[Corvallis, Oregon|Corvallis]], [[Hillsboro, Oregon|Hillsboro]] and [[Newberg/McMinnville, Oregon|Newberg/McMinnville]]. <ref>https://traveloregon.com/places-to-go/regions/willamette-valley/</ref>\n\nThe valley's numerous waterways, particularly the Willamette River, are vital to the economy of Oregon, as they continuously deposit highly fertile [[Alluvium|alluvial]] soils across its broad, flat plain. A massively productive agricultural area, the valley was widely publicized in the 1820s as a \"promised land of flowing milk and honey\". Throughout the 19th century it was the destination of choice for the oxen-drawn [[wagon train]]s of emigrants who made the perilous journey along the [[Oregon Trail]].\n\nToday the valley is often considered synonymous with \"Oregon Wine Country\", as it contains more than {{convert|19,000|acres|}} of vineyards and [[Willamette Valley AVA|500+ wineries]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://willamettewines.com/facts-figures|title=Willamette Valley Facts and Figures - Willamette Valley Wineries|author=|date=|website=willamettewines.com|accessdate=29 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Geology==\nMuch of the Willamette's fertility is derived from a series of massive ice-age floods that came from [[Lake Missoula]] in [[Montana]] and scoured across [[Eastern Washington]], sweeping its topsoil down the [[Columbia River Gorge]]. When floodwaters met log- and ice-jams at [[Kalama, Washington|Kalama]] in southwest Washington, the water caused a backup that filled the entire Willamette Valley to a depth of {{convert|300|to|400|ft|m}} above current sea level.<ref name=Cataclysms>''Cataclysms on the Columbia'', by John Elliott Allen and Marjorie Burns with Sam C. Sargent, 1986. Pages 175\u2013189.</ref> Some geologists suggest that the Willamette Valley flooded in this manner multiple times during the last ice age.<ref name=Cataclysms/><ref name=Oregon>''Geology of Oregon'', by Elizabeth L. Orr, William N. Orr and Ewart M. Baldwin, 1964. Pages 211\u2013214.</ref> If floodwaters of that magnitude covered Portland (elevation {{convert|20|ft|m}}) in 2010, only the tops of the [[Tualatin Mountains|West Hills]], Mount Tabor, Rocky Butte, Kelley Butte and Mount Scott would be visible,<ref name=Oregon/> as would only some of the city's tallest skyscrapers. Elevations for other cities in the valley are [[Newberg, Oregon|Newberg]], {{convert|175|ft|m}}; [[Oregon City, Oregon|Oregon City]], {{convert|138|ft|m}}; [[McMinnville, Oregon|McMinnville]], {{convert|157|ft|m}}; [[Salem, Oregon|Salem]], {{convert|154|ft|m}}; [[Corvallis, Oregon|Corvallis]], {{convert|235|ft|m}}; and [[Eugene, Oregon|Eugene]], {{convert|430|ft|m}}.  The lake gradually drained away, leaving layered sedimentary soils on the valley floor to a height of about {{convert|180|to|200|ft|m}} above current sea level throughout the [[Tualatin Valley|Tualatin]], [[Yamhill River|Yamhill]] and Willamette valleys.<ref name=Oregon/>\n\nGeologists have come to refer to the resulting lake as [[Lake Allison]], named for [[Oregon State University]] geologist [[Ira S. Allison]], who first described Willamette Silt soil in 1953 and noted its similarity to soils on the floor of former [[Lake Lewis]] in Eastern Washington. Allison is also known for his work in the 1930s documenting the hundreds of non-native boulders (called [[Glacial erratic|erratics]]) washed down by the floods, rafted on [[iceberg]]s and deposited on the valley bottom and in a ring around the lower hills surrounding the Willamette Valley. One of the most prominent of these is the [[Erratic Rock State Natural Site|Bellevue Erratic]], just off [[Oregon Route 18]] west of McMinnville.<ref name=Cataclysms/>\n\nIt is also believed that the [[Willamette Meteorite]] was rafted by flood and ice to the location near [[West Linn, Oregon|West Linn]] where it was found in 1902.\n\n==Geography==\nThe valley may be loosely defined as the broad plain of the Willamette, bounded on the west by the Oregon Coast Range and on the east by the Cascade Range. It is bounded on the south by the Calapooya Mountains, which separate the headwaters of the Willamette from the [[Umpqua River]] valley about {{convert|25|mi|km|0}} south of [[Hidden Valley, Oregon|Hidden Valley]].  [[Interstate 5]] runs the length of the valley, linking its major communities.\n\nBecause of differing cultural and political interests, the [[Portland metropolitan area]] and [[Tualatin Valley|Tualatin River valley]] are often not included in the local use of the term.  Additionally, the east slopes of the Coast Ranges and the west slopes of the Cascade Range from [[Oakridge, Oregon|Oakridge]] to [[Detroit Lake]] can be considered part of the Willamette Valley in a cultural sense, despite being mountainous areas.\n\nCities in the valley include, from south to north, [[Cottage Grove, Oregon|Cottage Grove]], Eugene, Corvallis, [[Albany, Oregon|Albany]], [[Dallas, Oregon|Dallas]], Salem, Keizer, McMinnville, and [[Hillsboro, Oregon|Hillsboro]]. Parts of the following counties, from south to north, lie within the valley: [[Douglas County, Oregon|Douglas]], [[Lane County, Oregon|Lane]], [[Linn County, Oregon|Linn]], [[Benton County, Oregon|Benton]], [[Polk County, Oregon|Polk]], [[Marion County, Oregon|Marion]], [[Yamhill County, Oregon|Yamhill]], and [[Washington County, Oregon|Washington]]. Sometimes the area around Albany and Corvallis and surrounding Benton and Linn counties is referred to locally as the Mid-Valley.<ref name=MVOnline>{{cite news |url= http://www.mvourtown.com/ |title= Mid-Valley Our Town |newspaper= [[Albany Democrat-Herald]] |accessdate= September 4, 2008}}</ref> Marion, Polk, and other counties are sometimes included in the definition of the Mid-Valley.\n\n==Climate==\n[[File:Willamette Valley fog.JPG|left|thumb|240px|alt=Fog in valley|Light fog in the southern valley]]\nThe climate of the Willamette Valley is a temperate oceanic '''climate''' (K\u00f6ppen ''Cfb''), which features cool summers, and wet winters with frequent overcast and cloudy skies. \n\nTemperatures are predictable throughout the year, with daytime highs frequently reaching the low to mid 80s in the summer and the mid 40s in the winter. Lengthy stretches of {{convert|90|F|C}} days occur every summer, occasionally reaching {{convert|100|F|C}}. Very cold days where the daytime high fails to rise above freezing are rare and may occur only two or three days per year, and occasionally not at all, especially in the lowest elevations of the valley. Temperatures of {{convert|5|F|C}} or lower occur only about once every 25 years. Spring and fall days are consistently between 50 and 70 degrees, with occasional surges of summer-like or winter-like temperatures that rarely last more than a week.<ref name = \"climatologist\"/>\n\nPrecipitation varies considerably across the valley and is closely correlated with elevation. Annual totals range from {{convert|36|in|mm}} at the lowest elevations to more than {{convert|80|in|mm}} in the foothills. Eugene, at the southern end of the valley, is {{convert|425|ft|m}} above sea level and receives 46 inches per year. Conversely, at the northern end of the valley, Portland is {{convert|50|ft|m}} above sea level and receives only 36 inches per year. Annual snow accumulation mimics this pattern, with most locations averaging {{convert|3|to|5|in|cm}} per year, although some winters receive no snowfall whatsoever.<ref name = \"climatologist\"/> Growing seasons are long, averaging 150 to 180 days per year in the lowlands to about 110 to 130 days at elevations above {{convert|800|ft|m}}.<ref name=\"climatologist\">{{cite web|last = Taylor|first = George|title = Climate of Multnomah County|publisher = Oregon Climate Service, Oregon State University|url = http://www.ocs.orst.edu/county_climate/Multnomah_files/Multnomah.html|accessdate = May 31, 2010|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100624153919/http://www.ocs.orst.edu/county_climate/Multnomah_files/Multnomah.html|archive-date = 2010-06-24|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nSevere storms of any kind are rare, although snow and ice storms can sometimes occur when surface low pressure systems move south along the coast, inducing offshore flow which advects cold air from the [[Columbia Plateau|Columbia Basin]] westward through the Columbia River Gorge, filling the valley to the north of the surface low track. Weather systems sometimes bring high winds to the northern region of the valley. Average cloud cover can exceed 70&nbsp;percent in winter but drops to less than 15&nbsp;percent in summer.<ref name = \"climatologist\"/> Willamette Valley tornadoes are rare, but do happen a few times a year with minimal damage. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/oregon-tornados-rare-dangerous/|title=Oregon Tornadoes Rare But Dangerous|last=Foden-Vencil|first=Kristian|website=www.opb.org|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>\n\n==Agriculture==\n[[File:Dahlias near Canby Oregon.JPG|thumb|right|upright|alt=Dahlia flowers|A field of [[Dahlias]] near [[Canby, Oregon|Canby]]]]\nThe agricultural richness of the valley is partly due to the [[Missoula Floods]] that inundated the valley approximately 40 times between 15,000 and 13,000&nbsp;years ago at the end of the last ice age. The floods were caused by the periodic rupturing of the ice dam of [[Glacial Lake Missoula]], the waters of which swept down the Columbia River and flooded the Willamette Valley as far south as Eugene. The floodwaters carried rich volcanic and glacial soil from [[Eastern Washington]], which was deposited across the valley floor when the waters subsided. The soil in the Willamette Valley is about {{convert|1/2|mi|km|0}} deep in some areas.<ref>{{cite book | last =Allen | first =John Eliot |author2=Burns, Marjorie |author3=Sargent, Sam C. | title =Cataclysms on the Columbia : a layman's guide to the features produced by the catastrophic Bretz floods in the Pacific Northwest | publisher =Timber Press | year =1986 | location =Portland, OR  | isbn =0-88192-067-3 | url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1510/is_n85/ai_17540025}}</ref>\n[[File:Autumn in the Vineyards (Yamhill County, Oregon scenic images) (yamDA0042).jpg|left|thumb|upright=0.50|alt=vineyard|Fall grape vines in a Willamette Valley vineyard]]\n\nIn the cool moist climate of the Willamette valley, over 170 different crop and livestock items are produced, including grass and legume seeds, tree fruits and nuts, wine grapes, berries, vegetables, nursery, Christmas trees, and field crops such as wheat, oats, mint and hops, hay, livestock and poultry and miscellaneous field crops. The valley also produces most of the cool-season forage and turf grass<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://oregonencyclopedia.org/articles/grass_seed_industry/#.XkeTsi2ZNN0|title=Grass seed industry|website=oregonencyclopedia.org|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>, [[Christmas tree]]s,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pnwcta.org/news-events/facts-at-a-glance/|title=Facts at a Glance {{!}} Pacific Northwest Christmas Tree Association|website=www.pnwcta.org|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref> and [[hazelnuts]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://oregonaitc.org/resources/oregon-resources/oregon-grown-commodities/hazelnuts/|title=Hazelnut Production Oregonaitc.org|author=|first=|date=|website=cornell.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=29 April 2018}}</ref> sold in North America. It is also noted for its [[hops]], which are widely used in [[craft beer]] and [[microbrewery|microbreweries]] throughout the U.S. \n\nIn recent decades, the valley has also become a major [[wine]] producer, with multiple [[American Viticultural Area]]s of its own. With a cooler [[climate]] than [[California]], the gently rolling hills surrounding the Willamette are home to some of the best (and most expensive) [[Pinot noir]] in the world, as well as a high-quality [[Pinot gris]].<ref>{{cite web\n | url = http://travel.latimes.com/articles/la-tr-oregonwineside5-2008oct05\n | title = Oregon's lush Willamette Valley offers a vintners' bounty\n | author = Patrick Comiskey\n | work = The Los Angeles Times\n | date = October 3, 2008\n | accessdate = March 29, 2010\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.vinography.com/archives/2009/06/the_best_pinot_noir_in_califor_1.html\n | title = The Best Pinot noir in California?: Tasting Pinot Days 2009\n | work = Vinography\n | date = June 29, 2009\n | accessdate = March 29, 2010\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n | title = Wine Spectator's Top 100 at a Glance\n | url = http://www.winespectator.com/Wine/Images/Graphics/Redesign/images/100_awards.pdf\n  | work = Wine Spectator\n | year = 2007\n |format = PDF\n | accessdate = July 13, 2010\n}}</ref> Although this distinction is not officially recognized, many wine connoisseurs further divide the Willamette Valley into northern and southern regions, the dividing line being the approximate latitude of Salem (approximately 45\u00b0 north latitude).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.answers.com/topic/willamette-valley-ava|title=Answers - The Most Trusted Place for Answering Life's Questions|work=Answers.com}}</ref> Not all portions of the Willamette Valley are suitable for vineyards, however, and the largest concentration of wineries is found west of the Willamette River, on the leeward slopes of the Coast Range, or among the numerous river and stream valleys created by Willamette River tributaries.  By far, the largest concentration of wineries is in Yamhill County.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.winesnw.com/nwillmap.html|title=Map page - Oregon's North Willamette Valley wine region and wineries|work=winesnw.com}}</ref>\n[[File:Harvesting hops near Independence, Oregon.jpg|right|thumb|upright|alt=Harvesting hops|Harvesting hops near Independence, Oregon, {{circa|1940}}]]\n\nGrass farmers have been [[Controlled burn#Agricultural use|burning fields]], as part of their production, since the 1940s. The smoke is often irritating to residents; in 1988 it caused a 23-car [[traffic collision|pileup]] on [[Interstate 5 in Oregon|I-5]]. Over the years, several pieces of legislation have limited the amount of burning permitted. With the passage of a bill championed by legislator [[Paul Holvey]] in the [[75th Oregon Legislative Assembly|2009 session]], burning has been banned since the summer of 2010, with the exception of an area of about {{convert|15,000|acre|km2|sigfig=1}} with steep terrain and certain species.<ref>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.paulholvey.com/_/2009_Bills.html\n | title = Chief Sponsored Bills\n | author =  Paul Holvey\n | work = Enacted Legislation Sponsored by Paul Holvey\n | accessdate = March 25, 2011\n}}</ref> (At its peak in the 1980s, about {{convert|250000|acre|km2|sigfig=1}} were burned each year.)<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Willamette Valley grass seed growers brace for future without field burning\n|first=Melissa\n|last=Repko\n|work=The Oregonian\n|date=July 17, 2009\n}}</ref>\n\nThe Marionberry, a cross between Chehalem and Olallie blackberries, was bred at Oregon State University as part of a berry-developing partnership with the U.S. Department of Agriculture that dates back to the early 1900s. It's named for Marion County in the Willamette Valley, where most of the field trials took place (not for former D.C. Mayor Marion Barry). When the berry was introduced in the 1950s, it was widely hailed as the most delicious blackberry commercial cultivar around. Even today, people rave over its tart-yet-sweet flavor \u2014 think of a cross between raspberries and blackberries. (Though there is some raspberry in its DNA, the red fruits are more like a genetic great-great grandparent to the marionberry.)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thesalt/2016/10/05/496462024/what-s-behind-oregon-s-marionberry-mania|title=What's Behind Oregon's Marionberry Mania?|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Ecology==\n[[File:Willamette River at Molalla SP eb.jpg|thumb|250px|alt=Willamette river|The Willamette River in the northern section of the valley]]\n{{main|Willamette Valley (ecoregion)}}\n\nThe Willamette Valley is prone to periodic floods.  Notable floods include the [[Great Flood of 1862]], events in 1899, the [[Christmas flood of 1964]], and the [[Willamette Valley Flood of 1996]].  Part of its [[floodplain]] is a [[National Natural Landmark]] called the [[Willamette Floodplain]].\n\nHistorically, the Willamette Valley forests were mostly an [[oak savanna]]\u2014tall grasslands with scattered [[Garry oak]]s and groves of [[coast Douglas-fir]]. The river floodplains contained extensive wetlands, stands of willow, alder, and cottonwood, and gallery forests. This landscape was maintained by the Native American inhabitants of the valley who set frequent fires that encouraged the open grasslands and killed young trees. The American settlers of the region, since the 19th&nbsp;century, suppressed fires and converted much of the valley to agriculture, which has caused much of the former grassland and savanna to revert to closed-canopy forest.  Less than one-tenth of one percent of the original savanna vegetation remains. The remaining enclaves include a section of Garry oak savanna preserved at [[Mount Pisgah Arboretum]] in Eugene. North Pacific Oak Woodland is a major forest alliance, extending through the Willamette Valley and southward to the Klamath Range of Northern California.<ref>C.Michael Hogan (2008) ''Quercus Kelloggii'', Globaltwitcher.com, ed. N. Stromberg [http://www.globaltwitcher.com/artspec_info.asp?thingid=82385]</ref> Many of the soils are well-drained [[Mesic habitat|mesic]].\n\n==Human history==\nHuman habitation in the Willamette Valley is estimated to have begun between 6,000 and 10,000 years ago.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oregon.gov/oprd/HCD/OHC/docs/multnomah_portland_sellwood_moreland_historiccontext.pdf|title=The Development of Sellwood-Moreland: History Context Statement of the Sellwood-Moreland Neighborhood, Portland, Oregon|last=Evans-Hatch|first=Gail E.H. and Michael Evans-Hatch|date=May 1999|website=Oregon.gov|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://greenbeltlandtrust.org/category/the-oak-savannas-of-home/|title=The Oak Savannas of Home|date=2012-09-04|work=Greenbelt Land Trust|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://ndnhistoryresearch.wordpress.com/2017/07/03/help-fund-my-book-project-tribal-stories-of-the-willamette-valley/|title=Help fund My Book Project: Tribal Stories of the Willamette Valley|last=Research|first=David G. Lewis' Ethnohistory|last2=LLC|date=2017-07-03|website=NDNHISTORYRESEARCH {{!}} Critical & Indigenous Anthropology|access-date=2017-07-05}}</ref> Until recently, the valley was largely inhabited by bands of the [[Kalapuya people|Kalapuya]] tribe of [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]].<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=http://libraryguides.lanecc.edu/kalapuya|title=LCC Research Guides: The Kalapuya: Native Americans of the Willamette Valley, Oregon: Home|last=Staff|first=Library|website=libraryguides.lanecc.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-07-05}}</ref> [[Molala language|Molala]] and [[Chinookan peoples|Chinook]] peoples also have inhabited portions of the Willamette Valley since time immemorial.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://libraryguides.lanecc.edu/chinookstories|title=LCC Research Guides: Stories of the Chinook People: Home|last=Staff|first=Library|website=libraryguides.lanecc.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-07-05}}</ref> Sixteen thousand Kalapuyans are estimated to have populated the valley as recently as the early 19th&nbsp;century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firescience.gov/projects/briefs/04-2-1-115_FSBrief98.pdf|title=\"Tracing the History of Fire in the Willamette Valley\"|last=Whitlock and Megan Walsh|first=Kathy|date=March 2010|website=Fire Science Brief|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref> As many as 90% of the Kalapuya may have died as a result of an epidemic of \"[[malaria|fever and ague]]\" that hit the area between 1830 and 1833.<ref name=\"Nch'i-Wana\">{{cite book|title=Nch'i-Wana, \"The Big River\"|last=Hunn|first=Eugene S.|publisher=[[University of Washington Press]]|year=1990|isbn=0-295-97119-3|pages=27\u201332}}</ref> Salmon, deer and [[camassia quamash|camas bulbs]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pdxscholar.library.pdx.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1021&context=open_access_etds|title=Exploring Prehistoric Salmon Subsistence in the Willamette Valley using Zooarchaeological Records and Optimal Foraging Theory|last=Elder|first=J. Tait|date=2010 |type=Dissertation and Theses. Paper 22|website=PDXScholar|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref> have provided primary food sources for the valley's first residents who used fire to encourage persistence of oak savanna. Oak trees have supplied another staple in the form of acorns which are leached, cooked and eaten.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Verne|first=Ray|date=May 1938|title=Lower Chinook Ethnographic Notes|url=http://cdm16786.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/ref/collection/lctext/id/1585|journal=University of Washington Publications in Anthropology|volume=7|issue=2|pages=29\u2013165|via=University of Washington Libraries}}</ref> [[Kalapuya]], [[Chinookan peoples|Chinook]] and [[Molala language|Molala]] peoples of the Willamette Valley currently are included among the confederated tribes that make up the [[Confederated Tribes of the Grand Ronde Community of Oregon|Grand Ronde]] and [[Confederated Tribes of Siletz Indians|Siletz]] Nations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ctsi.nsn.us/chinook-indian-tribe-siletz-heritage/our-history/part-i|title=Siletz Indian Tribe History, Tillamook Oregon, Multnomah County Oregon, Salishan - Part I - Introduction|website=www.ctsi.nsn.us|access-date=2017-07-05}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n[[File:Pioneer Mothers Memorial Cabin Museum.JPG|thumb|left|200px|alt=cabin|Pioneer cabin at Champoeg]]\n\nAfter reports of the [[Lewis and Clark Expedition]] were published in about 1807, a small and steadily increasing stream of isolated pioneer groups began settling the valley and improving routes from the east set up by [[fur trade]]rs and [[mountain men]]. From the 1841 [[Oregon Trail]] opening, when the effort of many years finally widened the fur traders' [[mule]] trails into an improved rough road just capable of carrying the width of a wagon, settlers charged into the region along the new trail, creating new settlements centered about [[Oregon City]] as the early capital, even before [[Oregon boundary dispute|ownership of the region]] was settled. So many people came that the valley led the way to achieving statehood less than 16 years after it was claimed by the United States in 1846. A small part of the Willamette Valley ecoregion is in southwestern [[Washington (state)|Washington]] around the city of [[Vancouver, Washington|Vancouver]], which was once the site of an early colonial-era settlement{{mdash}}[[Fort Vancouver]]. The Willamette Valley{{mdash}}served with its sawmills, lush productive farms, handy river transport network, and nearby timber and mineral resources{{mdash}}developed naturally as a cultural and major commercial hub, as the [[Oregon Country]] became the Oregon Territory.\n\nThe [[Hudson's Bay Company]] controlled the fur trade in the valley and the rest of Oregon Country in the 1820s and 1830s from its [[Columbia District]] headquarters at Fort Vancouver.  Joint U.S.\u2013British occupancy, in effect since the [[Treaty of 1818]], ended in 1846 with the [[Oregon Treaty]].\n\nThe Willamette Valley was connected to California's [[Central Valley (California)|Central Valley]] by the [[Siskiyou Trail]]. The first European settlements in the valley were at Oregon City and [[Champoeg, Oregon|Champoeg]]. The first institution of higher learning on the [[West Coast of the United States|West Coast]], today's [[Willamette University]], was founded in the valley at Salem by [[Jason Lee (missionary)|Jason Lee]], one of the many [[Oregon missionaries]] who settled in the valley.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Willamette Valley (ecoregion)]]\n* [[Willamette Valley AVA]] (wine region)\n* [[Jory (soil)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Works cited===\n* Loy, William G., ed.; Allan, Stuart; Buckley, Aileen R.; and Meacham, James E. (2001). ''Atlas of Oregon'', 2nd ed. Eugene, Oregon: University of Oregon Press. {{ISBN|0-87114-101-9}}.\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|author=MacGibbon, Elma|title=Leaves of knowledge|url=http://www.secstate.wa.gov/history/publications%5Fdetail.aspx?p=63|publisher=Shaw & Borden Co|year=1904}} Elma MacGibbons reminiscences of her travels in the United States starting in 1898, which were mainly in Oregon and Washington. Includes chapter \"Willamette Valley.\"\n* O'Connor, J.E., et al. (2001). Origin, extent, and thickness of Quaternary geologic units in the Willamette Valley, Oregon [U.S. Geological Survey Professional Paper 1620]. Reston, VA: U.S. Department of the Interior, U.S. Geological Survey.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [http://willametteexplorer.info/ The Willamette Basin Explorer] from [[Oregon State University]]\n* [http://willamettevalleyagriculture.wikidot.com/ Willamette Valley Agriculture] from [[Willamette University]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170712044355/http://willamettevalleydailyphoto.specialweb.com/ Willamette Valley Daily Photo]\n\n{{Oregon}}\n\n{{Coord|44.9|-123.1|region:US-OR_dim:200000|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Willamette Valley| ]]\n[[Category:Willamette River]]\n[[Category:Valleys of Oregon]]\n[[Category:Regions of Oregon]]\n[[Category:Agriculture in Oregon]]\n[[Category:River valleys of the United States]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Douglas County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Lane County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Benton County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Linn County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Polk County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Marion County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Clackamas County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Yamhill County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Washington County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Multnomah County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Columbia County, Oregon]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|valley in the Pacific Northwest region of the United States}}\n{{About|the geographic feature}}\n{{Infobox valley\n| name            = Willamette Valley\n| other_name      = \n| photo           =  Wvatbethel1.jpg \n| photo_caption   = Farmscape in northern [[Polk County, Oregon|Polk County]]\n<!-- MAP -->\n| map_image       = Small-Oregon-Map.png\n| map_caption     = The Willamette Valley contains most of Oregon's population; it extends from Newberg in the north to Eugene in the south.\n| location        = [[United States]], [[Oregon]]\n| relief          = \n| label           = \n| label_position  = \n| coordinates     = {{coord}}\n| coordinates_ref = \n<!-- Statistics -->  \n| elevation       = \n| elevation_m     = \n| elevation_ft    = \n| elevation_ref   = \n| direction       = \n| length          = \n| width           = \n| area            = \n| depth           = \n| type            = \n| age             = \n| boundaries      = [[Cascade Range]] (East)<br>[[Oregon Coast Range]] (West)<br>[[Calapooya Mountains]] (South)\n| topo            = \n| towns           = \n| traversed       = \n| watercourses    = [[Willamette River]]\n<!-- Below --> \n| footnotes       = \n| embed           = \n}}\n[[File:Wpdms shdrlfi020l willamette valley.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Willamette Valley [[drainage basin|basin]]]]\nThe '''Willamette Valley''' ({{IPAc-en|w|\u1d7b|\u02c8|l|\u00e6|m|\u1d7b|t}}) is a {{convert|150|mi|km|adj=on}} long valley in [[Oregon]], in the [[Pacific Northwest]] region of the [[United States]]. The [[Willamette River]] flows the entire length of the valley, and it is surrounded by mountains on three sides \u2013 the [[Cascade Range]] to the east, the [[Oregon Coast Range]] to the west, and the [[Calapooya Mountains]] to the south. \n\nThe valley is synonymous with the cultural and political heart of Oregon, and is home to approximately 70&nbsp;percent of its population<ref>Loy, ''et al.'', p. 35</ref> including the six largest cities in the state: [[Portland]], [[Eugene, Oregon|Eugene]], [[Salem, Oregon|Salem]], [[Corvallis, Oregon|Corvallis]], [[Hillsboro, Oregon|Hillsboro]] and [[Newberg/McMinnville, Oregon|Newberg/McMinnville]]. <ref>https://traveloregon.com/places-to-go/regions/willamette-valley/</ref>\n\nThe valley's numerous waterways, particularly the Willamette River, are vital to the economy of Oregon, as they continuously deposit highly fertile [[Alluvium|alluvial]] soils across its broad, flat plain. A massively productive agricultural area, the valley was widely publicized in the 1820s as a \"promised land of flowing milk and honey\". Throughout the 19th century it was the destination of choice for the oxen-drawn [[wagon train]]s of emigrants who made the perilous journey along the [[Oregon Trail]].\n\nToday the valley is often considered synonymous with \"Oregon Wine Country\", as it contains more than {{convert|19,000|acres|}} of vineyards and [[Willamette Valley AVA|500+ wineries]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://willamettewines.com/facts-figures|title=Willamette Valley Facts and Figures - Willamette Valley Wineries|author=|date=|website=willamettewines.com|accessdate=29 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Geology==\nMuch of the Willamette's fertility is derived from a series of massive ice-age floods that came from [[Lake Missoula]] in [[Montana]] and scoured across [[Eastern Washington]], sweeping its topsoil down the [[Columbia River Gorge]]. When floodwaters met log- and ice-jams at [[Kalama, Washington|Kalama]] in southwest Washington, the water caused a backup that filled the entire Willamette Valley to a depth of {{convert|300|to|400|ft|m}} above current sea level.<ref name=Cataclysms>''Cataclysms on the Columbia'', by John Elliott Allen and Marjorie Burns with Sam C. Sargent, 1986. Pages 175\u2013189.</ref> Some geologists suggest that the Willamette Valley flooded in this manner multiple times during the last ice age.<ref name=Cataclysms/><ref name=Oregon>''Geology of Oregon'', by Elizabeth L. Orr, William N. Orr and Ewart M. Baldwin, 1964. Pages 211\u2013214.</ref> If floodwaters of that magnitude covered Portland (elevation {{convert|20|ft|m}}) in 2010, only the tops of the [[Tualatin Mountains|West Hills]], Mount Tabor, Rocky Butte, Kelley Butte and Mount Scott would be visible,<ref name=Oregon/> as would only some of the city's tallest skyscrapers. Elevations for other cities in the valley are [[Newberg, Oregon|Newberg]], {{convert|175|ft|m}}; [[Oregon City, Oregon|Oregon City]], {{convert|138|ft|m}}; [[McMinnville, Oregon|McMinnville]], {{convert|157|ft|m}}; [[Salem, Oregon|Salem]], {{convert|154|ft|m}}; [[Corvallis, Oregon|Corvallis]], {{convert|235|ft|m}}; and [[Eugene, Oregon|Eugene]], {{convert|430|ft|m}}.  The lake gradually drained away, leaving layered sedimentary soils on the valley floor to a height of about {{convert|180|to|200|ft|m}} above current sea level throughout the [[Tualatin Valley|Tualatin]], [[Yamhill River|Yamhill]] and Willamette valleys.<ref name=Oregon/>\n\nGeologists have come to refer to the resulting lake as [[Lake Allison]], named for [[Oregon State University]] geologist [[Ira S. Allison]], who first described Willamette Silt soil in 1953 and noted its similarity to soils on the floor of former [[Lake Lewis]] in Eastern Washington. Allison is also known for his work in the 1930s documenting the hundreds of non-native boulders (called [[Glacial erratic|erratics]]) washed down by the floods, rafted on [[iceberg]]s and deposited on the valley bottom and in a ring around the lower hills surrounding the Willamette Valley. One of the most prominent of these is the [[Erratic Rock State Natural Site|Bellevue Erratic]], just off [[Oregon Route 18]] west of McMinnville.<ref name=Cataclysms/>\n\nIt is also believed that the [[Willamette Meteorite]] was rafted by flood and ice to the location near [[West Linn, Oregon|West Linn]] where it was found in 1902.\n\n==Geography==\nThe valley may be loosely defined as the broad plain of the Willamette, bounded on the west by the Oregon Coast Range and on the east by the Cascade Range. It is bounded on the south by the Calapooya Mountains, which separate the headwaters of the Willamette from the [[Umpqua River]] valley about {{convert|25|mi|km|0}} south of [[Hidden Valley, Oregon|Hidden Valley]].  [[Interstate 5]] runs the length of the valley, linking its major communities.\n\nBecause of differing cultural and political interests, the [[Portland metropolitan area]] and [[Tualatin Valley|Tualatin River valley]] are often not included in the local use of the term.  Additionally, the east slopes of the Coast Ranges and the west slopes of the Cascade Range from [[Oakridge, Oregon|Oakridge]] to [[Detroit Lake]] can be considered part of the Willamette Valley in a cultural sense, despite being mountainous areas.\n\nCities in the valley include, from south to north, [[Cottage Grove, Oregon|Cottage Grove]], Eugene, Corvallis, [[Albany, Oregon|Albany]], [[Dallas, Oregon|Dallas]], Salem, Keizer, McMinnville, and [[Hillsboro, Oregon|Hillsboro]]. Parts of the following counties, from south to north, lie within the valley: [[Douglas County, Oregon|Douglas]], [[Lane County, Oregon|Lane]], [[Linn County, Oregon|Linn]], [[Benton County, Oregon|Benton]], [[Polk County, Oregon|Polk]], [[Marion County, Oregon|Marion]], [[Yamhill County, Oregon|Yamhill]], and [[Washington County, Oregon|Washington]]. Sometimes the area around Albany and Corvallis and surrounding Benton and Linn counties is referred to locally as the Mid-Valley.<ref name=MVOnline>{{cite news |url= http://www.mvourtown.com/ |title= Mid-Valley Our Town |newspaper= [[Albany Democrat-Herald]] |accessdate= September 4, 2008}}</ref> Marion, Polk, and other counties are sometimes included in the definition of the Mid-Valley.\n\n==Climate==\n[[File:Willamette Valley fog.JPG|left|thumb|240px|alt=Fog in valley|Light fog in the southern valley]]\nThe climate of the Willamette Valley is a temperate oceanic '''climate''' (K\u00f6ppen ''Cfb''), which features cool summers, and wet winters with frequent overcast and cloudy skies. \n\nTemperatures are predictable throughout the year, with daytime highs frequently reaching the low to mid 80s in the summer and the mid 40s in the winter. Lengthy stretches of {{convert|90|F|C}} days occur every summer, occasionally reaching {{convert|100|F|C}}. Very cold days where the daytime high fails to rise above freezing are rare and may occur only two or three days per year, and occasionally not at all, especially in the lowest elevations of the valley. Temperatures of {{convert|5|F|C}} or lower occur only about once every 25 years. Spring and fall days are consistently between 50 and 70 degrees, with occasional surges of summer-like or winter-like temperatures that rarely last more than a week.<ref name = \"climatologist\"/>\n\nPrecipitation varies considerably across the valley and is closely correlated with elevation. Annual totals range from {{convert|36|in|mm}} at the lowest elevations to more than {{convert|80|in|mm}} in the foothills. Eugene, at the southern end of the valley, is {{convert|425|ft|m}} above sea level and receives 46 inches per year. Conversely, at the northern end of the valley, Portland is {{convert|50|ft|m}} above sea level and receives only 36 inches per year. Annual snow accumulation mimics this pattern, with most locations averaging {{convert|3|to|5|in|cm}} per year, although some winters receive no snowfall whatsoever.<ref name = \"climatologist\"/> Growing seasons are long, averaging 150 to 180 days per year in the lowlands to about 110 to 130 days at elevations above {{convert|800|ft|m}}.<ref name=\"climatologist\">{{cite web|last = Taylor|first = George|title = Climate of Multnomah County|publisher = Oregon Climate Service, Oregon State University|url = http://www.ocs.orst.edu/county_climate/Multnomah_files/Multnomah.html|accessdate = May 31, 2010|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100624153919/http://www.ocs.orst.edu/county_climate/Multnomah_files/Multnomah.html|archive-date = 2010-06-24|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nSevere storms of any kind are rare, although snow and ice storms can sometimes occur when surface low pressure systems move south along the coast, inducing offshore flow which advects cold air from the [[Columbia Plateau|Columbia Basin]] westward through the Columbia River Gorge, filling the valley to the north of the surface low track. Weather systems sometimes bring high winds to the northern region of the valley. Average cloud cover can exceed 70&nbsp;percent in winter but drops to less than 15&nbsp;percent in summer.<ref name = \"climatologist\"/> Willamette Valley tornadoes are rare, but do happen a few times a year with minimal damage. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/oregon-tornados-rare-dangerous/|title=Oregon Tornadoes Rare But Dangerous|last=Foden-Vencil|first=Kristian|website=www.opb.org|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>\n\n==Agriculture==\n[[File:Dahlias near Canby Oregon.JPG|thumb|right|upright|alt=Dahlia flowers|A field of [[Dahlias]] near [[Canby, Oregon|Canby]]]]\nThe agricultural richness of the valley is partly due to the [[Missoula Floods]] that inundated the valley approximately 40 times between 15,000 and 13,000&nbsp;years ago at the end of the last ice age. The floods were caused by the periodic rupturing of the ice dam of [[Glacial Lake Missoula]], the waters of which swept down the Columbia River and flooded the Willamette Valley as far south as Eugene. The floodwaters carried rich volcanic and glacial soil from [[Eastern Washington]], which was deposited across the valley floor when the waters subsided. The soil in the Willamette Valley is about {{convert|1/2|mi|km|0}} deep in some areas.<ref>{{cite book | last =Allen | first =John Eliot |author2=Burns, Marjorie |author3=Sargent, Sam C. | title =Cataclysms on the Columbia : a layman's guide to the features produced by the catastrophic Bretz floods in the Pacific Northwest | publisher =Timber Press | year =1986 | location =Portland, OR  | isbn =0-88192-067-3 | url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1510/is_n85/ai_17540025}}</ref>\n[[File:Autumn in the Vineyards (Yamhill County, Oregon scenic images) (yamDA0042).jpg|left|thumb|upright=0.50|alt=vineyard|Fall grape vines in a Willamette Valley vineyard]]\n\nIn the cool moist climate of the Willamette valley, over 170 different crop and livestock items are produced, including grass and legume seeds, tree fruits and nuts, wine grapes, berries, vegetables, nursery, Christmas trees, and field crops such as wheat, oats, mint and hops, hay, livestock and poultry and miscellaneous field crops. The valley also produces most of the cool-season forage and turf grass<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://oregonencyclopedia.org/articles/grass_seed_industry/#.XkeTsi2ZNN0|title=Grass seed industry|website=oregonencyclopedia.org|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>, [[Christmas tree]]s,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pnwcta.org/news-events/facts-at-a-glance/|title=Facts at a Glance {{!}} Pacific Northwest Christmas Tree Association|website=www.pnwcta.org|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref> and [[hazelnuts]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://oregonaitc.org/resources/oregon-resources/oregon-grown-commodities/hazelnuts/|title=Hazelnut Production Oregonaitc.org|author=|first=|date=|website=cornell.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=29 April 2018}}</ref> sold in North America. It is also noted for its [[hops]], which are widely used in [[craft beer]] and [[microbrewery|microbreweries]] throughout the U.S. \n\nIn recent decades, the valley has also become a major [[wine]] producer, with multiple [[American Viticultural Area]]s of its own. With a cooler [[climate]] than [[California]], the gently rolling hills surrounding the Willamette are home to some of the best (and most expensive) [[Pinot noir]] in the world, as well as a high-quality [[Pinot gris]].<ref>{{cite web\n | url = http://travel.latimes.com/articles/la-tr-oregonwineside5-2008oct05\n | title = Oregon's lush Willamette Valley offers a vintners' bounty\n | author = Patrick Comiskey\n | work = The Los Angeles Times\n | date = October 3, 2008\n | accessdate = March 29, 2010\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.vinography.com/archives/2009/06/the_best_pinot_noir_in_califor_1.html\n | title = The Best Pinot noir in California?: Tasting Pinot Days 2009\n | work = Vinography\n | date = June 29, 2009\n | accessdate = March 29, 2010\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n | title = Wine Spectator's Top 100 at a Glance\n | url = http://www.winespectator.com/Wine/Images/Graphics/Redesign/images/100_awards.pdf\n  | work = Wine Spectator\n | year = 2007\n |format = PDF\n | accessdate = July 13, 2010\n}}</ref> Although this distinction is not officially recognized, many wine connoisseurs further divide the Willamette Valley into northern and southern regions, the dividing line being the approximate latitude of Salem (approximately 45\u00b0 north latitude).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.answers.com/topic/willamette-valley-ava|title=Answers - The Most Trusted Place for Answering Life's Questions|work=Answers.com}}</ref> Not all portions of the Willamette Valley are suitable for vineyards, however, and the largest concentration of wineries is found west of the Willamette River, on the leeward slopes of the Coast Range, or among the numerous river and stream valleys created by Willamette River tributaries.  By far, the largest concentration of wineries is in Yamhill County.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.winesnw.com/nwillmap.html|title=Map page - Oregon's North Willamette Valley wine region and wineries|work=winesnw.com}}</ref>\n[[File:Harvesting hops near Independence, Oregon.jpg|right|thumb|upright|alt=Harvesting hops|Harvesting hops near Independence, Oregon, {{circa|1940}}]]\n\nGrass farmers have been [[Controlled burn#Agricultural use|burning fields]], as part of their production, since the 1940s. The smoke is often irritating to residents; in 1988 it caused a 23-car [[traffic collision|pileup]] on [[Interstate 5 in Oregon|I-5]]. Over the years, several pieces of legislation have limited the amount of burning permitted. With the passage of a bill championed by legislator [[Paul Holvey]] in the [[75th Oregon Legislative Assembly|2009 session]], burning has been banned since the summer of 2010, with the exception of an area of about {{convert|15,000|acre|km2|sigfig=1}} with steep terrain and certain species.<ref>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.paulholvey.com/_/2009_Bills.html\n | title = Chief Sponsored Bills\n | author =  Paul Holvey\n | work = Enacted Legislation Sponsored by Paul Holvey\n | accessdate = March 25, 2011\n}}</ref> (At its peak in the 1980s, about {{convert|250000|acre|km2|sigfig=1}} were burned each year.)<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Willamette Valley grass seed growers brace for future without field burning\n|first=Melissa\n|last=Repko\n|work=The Oregonian\n|date=July 17, 2009\n}}</ref>\n\nThe Marionberry, a cross between Chehalem and Olallie blackberries, was bred at Oregon State University as part of a berry-developing partnership with the U.S. Department of Agriculture that dates back to the early 1900s. It's named for Marion County in the Willamette Valley, where most of the field trials took place (not for former D.C. Mayor Marion Barry). When the berry was introduced in the 1950s, it was widely hailed as the most delicious blackberry commercial cultivar around. Even today, people rave over its tart-yet-sweet flavor \u2014 think of a cross between raspberries and blackberries. (Though there is some raspberry in its DNA, the red fruits are more like a genetic great-great grandparent to the marionberry.)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thesalt/2016/10/05/496462024/what-s-behind-oregon-s-marionberry-mania|title=What's Behind Oregon's Marionberry Mania?|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Ecology==\n[[File:Willamette River at Molalla SP eb.jpg|thumb|250px|alt=Willamette river|The Willamette River in the northern section of the valley]]\n{{main|Willamette Valley (ecoregion)}}\n\nThe Willamette Valley is prone to periodic floods.  Notable floods include the [[Great Flood of 1862]], events in 1899, the [[Christmas flood of 1964]], and the [[Willamette Valley Flood of 1996]].  Part of its [[floodplain]] is a [[National Natural Landmark]] called the [[Willamette Floodplain]].\n\nHistorically, the Willamette Valley forests were mostly an [[oak savanna]]\u2014tall grasslands with scattered [[Garry oak]]s and groves of [[coast Douglas-fir]]. The river floodplains contained extensive wetlands, stands of willow, alder, and cottonwood, and gallery forests. This landscape was maintained by the Native American inhabitants of the valley who set frequent fires that encouraged the open grasslands and killed young trees. The American settlers of the region, since the 19th&nbsp;century, suppressed fires and converted much of the valley to agriculture, which has caused much of the former grassland and savanna to revert to closed-canopy forest.  Less than one-tenth of one percent of the original savanna vegetation remains. The remaining enclaves include a section of Garry oak savanna preserved at [[Mount Pisgah Arboretum]] in Eugene. North Pacific Oak Woodland is a major forest alliance, extending through the Willamette Valley and southward to the Klamath Range of Northern California.<ref>C.Michael Hogan (2008) ''Quercus Kelloggii'', Globaltwitcher.com, ed. N. Stromberg [http://www.globaltwitcher.com/artspec_info.asp?thingid=82385]</ref> Many of the soils are well-drained [[Mesic habitat|mesic]].\n\n==Human history==\nHuman habitation in the Willamette Valley is estimated to have begun between 6,000 and 10,000 years ago.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oregon.gov/oprd/HCD/OHC/docs/multnomah_portland_sellwood_moreland_historiccontext.pdf|title=The Development of Sellwood-Moreland: History Context Statement of the Sellwood-Moreland Neighborhood, Portland, Oregon|last=Evans-Hatch|first=Gail E.H. and Michael Evans-Hatch|date=May 1999|website=Oregon.gov|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://greenbeltlandtrust.org/category/the-oak-savannas-of-home/|title=The Oak Savannas of Home|date=2012-09-04|work=Greenbelt Land Trust|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://ndnhistoryresearch.wordpress.com/2017/07/03/help-fund-my-book-project-tribal-stories-of-the-willamette-valley/|title=Help fund My Book Project: Tribal Stories of the Willamette Valley|last=Research|first=David G. Lewis' Ethnohistory|last2=LLC|date=2017-07-03|website=NDNHISTORYRESEARCH {{!}} Critical & Indigenous Anthropology|access-date=2017-07-05}}</ref> Until recently, the valley was largely inhabited by bands of the [[Kalapuya people|Kalapuya]] tribe of [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]].<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=http://libraryguides.lanecc.edu/kalapuya|title=LCC Research Guides: The Kalapuya: Native Americans of the Willamette Valley, Oregon: Home|last=Staff|first=Library|website=libraryguides.lanecc.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-07-05}}</ref> [[Molala language|Molala]] and [[Chinookan peoples|Chinook]] peoples also have inhabited portions of the Willamette Valley since time immemorial.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://libraryguides.lanecc.edu/chinookstories|title=LCC Research Guides: Stories of the Chinook People: Home|last=Staff|first=Library|website=libraryguides.lanecc.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-07-05}}</ref> Sixteen thousand Kalapuyans are estimated to have populated the valley as recently as the early 19th&nbsp;century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firescience.gov/projects/briefs/04-2-1-115_FSBrief98.pdf|title=\"Tracing the History of Fire in the Willamette Valley\"|last=Whitlock and Megan Walsh|first=Kathy|date=March 2010|website=Fire Science Brief|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref> As many as 90% of the Kalapuya may have died as a result of an epidemic of \"[[malaria|fever and ague]]\" that hit the area between 1830 and 1833.<ref name=\"Nch'i-Wana\">{{cite book|title=Nch'i-Wana, \"The Big River\"|last=Hunn|first=Eugene S.|publisher=[[University of Washington Press]]|year=1990|isbn=0-295-97119-3|pages=27\u201332}}</ref> Salmon, deer and [[camassia quamash|camas bulbs]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pdxscholar.library.pdx.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1021&context=open_access_etds|title=Exploring Prehistoric Salmon Subsistence in the Willamette Valley using Zooarchaeological Records and Optimal Foraging Theory|last=Elder|first=J. Tait|date=2010 |type=Dissertation and Theses. Paper 22|website=PDXScholar|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref> have provided primary food sources for the valley's first residents who used fire to encourage persistence of oak savanna. Oak trees have supplied another staple in the form of acorns which are leached, cooked and eaten.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Verne|first=Ray|date=May 1938|title=Lower Chinook Ethnographic Notes|url=http://cdm16786.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/ref/collection/lctext/id/1585|journal=University of Washington Publications in Anthropology|volume=7|issue=2|pages=29\u2013165|via=University of Washington Libraries}}</ref> [[Kalapuya]], [[Chinookan peoples|Chinook]] and [[Molala language|Molala]] peoples of the Willamette Valley currently are included among the confederated tribes that make up the [[Confederated Tribes of the Grand Ronde Community of Oregon|Grand Ronde]] and [[Confederated Tribes of Siletz Indians|Siletz]] Nations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ctsi.nsn.us/chinook-indian-tribe-siletz-heritage/our-history/part-i|title=Siletz Indian Tribe History, Tillamook Oregon, Multnomah County Oregon, Salishan - Part I - Introduction|website=www.ctsi.nsn.us|access-date=2017-07-05}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n[[File:Pioneer Mothers Memorial Cabin Museum.JPG|thumb|left|200px|alt=cabin|Pioneer cabin at Champoeg]]\n\nAfter reports of the [[Lewis and Clark Expedition]] were published in about 1807, a small and steadily increasing stream of isolated pioneer groups began settling the valley and improving routes from the east set up by [[fur trade]]rs and [[mountain men]]. From the 1841 [[Oregon Trail]] opening, when the effort of many years finally widened the fur traders' [[mule]] trails into an improved rough road just capable of carrying the width of a wagon, settlers charged into the region along the new trail, creating new settlements centered about [[Oregon City]] as the early capital, even before [[Oregon boundary dispute|ownership of the region]] was settled. So many people came that the valley led the way to achieving statehood less than 16 years after it was claimed by the United States in 1846. A small part of the Willamette Valley ecoregion is in southwestern [[Washington (state)|Washington]] around the city of [[Vancouver, Washington|Vancouver]], which was once the site of an early colonial-era settlement{{mdash}}[[Fort Vancouver]]. The Willamette Valley{{mdash}}served with its sawmills, lush productive farms, handy river transport network, and nearby timber and mineral resources{{mdash}}developed naturally as a cultural and major commercial hub, as the [[Oregon Country]] became the Oregon Territory.\n\nThe [[Hudson's Bay Company]] controlled the fur trade in the valley and the rest of Oregon Country in the 1820s and 1830s from its [[Columbia District]] headquarters at Fort Vancouver.  Joint U.S.\u2013British occupancy, in effect since the [[Treaty of 1818]], ended in 1846 with the [[Oregon Treaty]].\n\nThe Willamette Valley was connected to California's [[Central Valley (California)|Central Valley]] by the [[Siskiyou Trail]]. The first European settlements in the valley were at Oregon City and [[Champoeg, Oregon|Champoeg]]. The first institution of higher learning on the [[West Coast of the United States|West Coast]], today's [[Willamette University]], was founded in the valley at Salem by [[Jason Lee (missionary)|Jason Lee]], one of the many [[Oregon missionaries]] who settled in the valley.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Willamette Valley (ecoregion)]]\n* [[Willamette Valley AVA]] (wine region)\n* [[Jory (soil)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Works cited===\n* Loy, William G., ed.; Allan, Stuart; Buckley, Aileen R.; and Meacham, James E. (2001). ''Atlas of Oregon'', 2nd ed. Eugene, Oregon: University of Oregon Press. {{ISBN|0-87114-101-9}}.\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|author=MacGibbon, Elma|title=Leaves of knowledge|url=http://www.secstate.wa.gov/history/publications%5Fdetail.aspx?p=63|publisher=Shaw & Borden Co|year=1904}} Elma MacGibbons reminiscences of her travels in the United States starting in 1898, which were mainly in Oregon and Washington. Includes chapter \"Willamette Valley.\"\n* O'Connor, J.E., et al. (2001). Origin, extent, and thickness of Quaternary geologic units in the Willamette Valley, Oregon [U.S. Geological Survey Professional Paper 1620]. Reston, VA: U.S. Department of the Interior, U.S. Geological Survey.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [http://willametteexplorer.info/ The Willamette Basin Explorer] from [[Oregon State University]]\n* [http://willamettevalleyagriculture.wikidot.com/ Willamette Valley Agriculture] from [[Willamette University]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170712044355/http://willamettevalleydailyphoto.specialweb.com/ Willamette Valley Daily Photo]\n\n{{Oregon}}\n\n{{Coord|44.9|-123.1|region:US-OR_dim:200000|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Willamette Valley| ]]\n[[Category:Willamette River]]\n[[Category:Valleys of Oregon]]\n[[Category:Regions of Oregon]]\n[[Category:Agriculture in Oregon]]\n[[Category:River valleys of the United States]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Douglas County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Lane County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Benton County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Linn County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Polk County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Marion County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Clackamas County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Yamhill County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Washington County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Multnomah County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Columbia County, Oregon]]\n", "name_user": "Funga", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed link in intro (porland to portland, OR)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Willamette_Valley"}
{"title_page": "Molly (name)", "text_new": "{{Infobox given name\n| name          = Molly\n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| caption       = \n| pronunciation = {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|m|\u0252|l|i}}\n| gender        = [[Unisex]]\n| meaning       = \n| region        = \n| language      = Irish and English\n| origin        = \n| alternative spelling = Mollie Moli \n| nickname      = Mols Mol\n| variant forms = \n| related names = \n| name day      = \n| derived       = {{ubl|[[Mary (given name)|Mary]]|[[Margaret (name)|Margaret]]}}\n| popularity    = \n| footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Molly''' (also spelled '''Molli''' or '''Mollie''') is a diminutive of the English feminine name [[Mary (name)|Mary]]. It may less commonly be used as a diminutive for popular feminine names that begin with M, such as [[Margaret]], [[Martha (given name)|Martha]], or [[Martina (given name)|Martina]] or Melinda. May be used as a masculine name, but it is less common.\n\n==People==\n===Men===\n* Malcolm [[Molly Duncan]] (1945\u20132019), Scottish tenor saxophonist, founding member of the Average White Band\n* [[Molly Meldrum|Ian \"Molly\" Meldrum]] (born 1943), Australian music critic, journalist, record producer and musical entrepreneur\n\n===Women===\n* [[Mollie Arline Kirkland Bailey]] (c. 1844\u20131918), American circus musician, singer, wartime nurse and alleged Confederate spy\n* [[Molly Bang]] (born 1943), American Illustrator\n* [[Martina Beck|Martina \"Molly\" Beck]] (born 1979), German retired biathlete\n* [[Molly Bee]] (1939\u20132009), stage name of Mollie Gene Beachboard, American country music singer\n* [[Molly Bish]] (1983\u20132000), American murder victim\n* [[Molly Brant]] (c. 1736\u20131796), prominent Mohawk woman in the era of the American Revolution\n* [[Margaret Brown|Margaret \"The Unsinkable Molly\" Brown]] (1867\u20131932), survivor of the [[sinking of the RMS Titanic]], philanthropist and activist\n* [[Molly Burnett]] (born 1988), American actress and singer\n* [[Molly Crabapple]] (n\u00e9e Jennifer Caban; born 1983), American artist and writer\n* [[Molly Dunsworth]] (born 1990), Canadian actress\n* [[Molly Engstrom]] (born 1983), American ice hockey player\n* [[Mollie Evans|Mary \"Mollie\" Evans]] (1922\u20132016), British antique dealer\n* [[Mollie Hardwick]] (1916\u20132003), English author\n* [[Molly Hawkey]] (born 1978), American actress and photographer\n* [[Molly Haskell]] (born 1939), American feminist film critic and author\n* [[Mary Vivian Hughes|Mary Vivian \"Molly\" Hughes]], British author\n* [[Mollie Hunter]] (1922\u20132012), Scottish writer\n* [[Molly Ivins|Mary \"Molly\" Ivins]] (1944\u20132007), American columnist, political commentator, humorist and author\n* [[Mollie Johnson]], 19th century American Old West madam in South Dakota\n* [[Molly Johnson|Margaret \"Molly\" Johnson]] (born 1959), Canadian singer and songwriter\n* [[M. M. Kaye]] (1908\u20132004), British writer, author of ''The Far Pavilions''\n* [[Mollie Katzen]] (born 1950), American chef and cookbook writer\n* [[Molly Keane|Mary \"Molly\" Keane]] (n\u00e9e Mary Nesta Skrine; 1904\u20131996), Irish novelist and playwright\n* [[Mollie King]] (born 1987), British singer with The Saturdays\n* [[Molly Lamont]] (1910\u20132001), South African-born British film actress\n* [[Mary MacCarthy]] (1882\u20131953), British writer associated with the \"Bloomsbury Group\"\n* [[Mollie McConnell]] (1865\u20131920), American theater and silent film actress\n* [[Molly Nyman]], British composer\n* [[Mollie Orshansky]] (1915\u20132006), American economist and statistician\n* [[Molly Parker]] (born 1972), Canadian actress\n* [[Molly Parkin]] (born 1932), Welsh painter, novelist and journalist\n* [[Molly Peacock]] (born 1947), American-Canadian poet, essayist and creative nonfiction writer\n* [[Molly Pearson]] (1875\u20131959), Scottish stage actress\n* [[Mollie Phillips]] (1907\u20131994), British figure skater\n* [[Molly Picon]] (n\u00e9e Ma\u0142ka Opiekun; 1898\u20131992), American actress in Yiddish theatre and film\n* [[Molly Pitcher]], nickname of a woman said to have fought in the American Revolutionary War Battle of Monmouth, generally believed to have been Mary Ludwig Hays McCauley\n* [[Molly Quinn]] (born 1993), American actress\n* [[Molly Ringwald]] (born 1968), American actress, singer, and dancer\n* [[Molly Sand\u00e9n]] (born 1992), Swedish singer\n* [[Molly Shannon]] (born 1964), American comic actress\n* [[Molly Shattuck]] (born c. 1967), American socialite and oldest NFL cheerleader\n* [[Molly Sims]] (born 1973), American model and actress\n* Mary [[Mollie Skinner]] (1876\u20131955), Australian Quaker, nurse and writer\n* [[Molly Smitten-Downes]] (born 1987), British singer-songwriter\n* [[Mollie Sneden|Mary \"Mollie\" Sneden]] (1709\u20131810), ferry operator before and after the American Revolution\n* [[Mollie Steimer|Marthe \"Mollie\" Steimer]] (1897\u20131980), Russian-American anarchist, trade unionist, anti-war activist and free-speech campaigner\n* [[Mollie Sugden]] (1922\u20132009), British actress\n* [[Mememolly]] (born Molly Templeton in 1989), English Internet personality\n* Mollie Tibbetts (1998-2018), American [[Killing of Mollie Tibbetts|murder victim]]\n* [[Molly Tuttle]] (born 1993), American singer and musician\n* [[Molly White]] (born 1958), American politician\n* [[Molly Wood]] (born 1975), American executive editor and writer\n\n==Fictional characters==\n\n===In television and film===\n* [[Molly Baker]], from ''Sailor Moon''\n* [[Molly Dobbs]], from ''Coronation Street''\n* [[List of Mike & Molly characters#Molly Flynn|Molly Flynn-Biggs]], from ''Mike & Molly''\n* [[Molly Hooper]], from ''Sherlock''\n* [[Molly Lansing]], from ''General Hospital''\n* [[Molly O'Brien]], from ''Star Trek: The Next Generation''\n* [[Molly Walker]], from ''Heroes''\n* [[Molly (Buffy the Vampire Slayer)|Molly (''Buffy the Vampire Slayer'')]]\n* [[Molly (Friends)|Molly (''Friends'')]]\n* [[Molly (Star-Racers)|Molly (''Star-Racers'')]]\n* [[Molly (The Big Comfy Couch)|Molly (''The Big Comfy Couch'')]]\n* [[Molly (Thomas the Tank Engine)|Molly (''Thomas the Tank Engine'')]]\n* [[Molly (Toy Story)|Molly (''Toy Story'')]]\n* Molly Williams, from [[My Little Pony (TV series)]]\n* Molly, from [[Annie (1982 film)]]\n* Molly, from [[Bubble Guppies]]\n* Molly, from [[The Basil Brush Show]]\n* [[List of Final Destination characters#Molly Harper|Molly Harper]], from ''Final Destination 5''\n* [[List of The Amazing World of Gumball characters#Molly Collins|Molly Collins]] from ''[[The Amazing World of Gumball]]''\n* [[Molly Weasley]] from [[Harry Potter]] series\n\n==Animals==\n*[[Polly and Molly]], cloned sheep\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Moll (disambiguation)]]\n\n{{given name}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Molly}}\n[[Category:English given names]]\n[[Category:Feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Hypocorisms]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox given name\n| name          = Molly\n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| caption       = \n| pronunciation = {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|m|\u0252|l|i}}\n| gender        = [[Unisex]]\n| meaning       = \n| region        = \n| language      = Irish and English\n| origin        = \n| alternative spelling = Mollie Moli \n| nickname      = Mols Mol\n| variant forms = \n| related names = \n| name day      = \n| derived       = {{ubl|[[Mary (given name)|Mary]]|[[Margaret (name)|Margaret]]}}\n| popularity    = \n| footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Molly''' (also spelled '''Molli''' or '''Mollie''') is a diminutive of the English feminine name [[Mary (name)|Mary]]. It may less commonly be used as a diminutive for popular feminine names that begin with M, such as [[Margaret]], [[Martha (given name)|Martha]], or [[Martina (given name)|Martina]] or Melinda. May be used as a masculine name, but it is less common.\n\n==People==\n===Men===\n* Malcolm [[Molly Duncan]] (1945\u20132019), Scottish tenor saxophonist, founding member of the Average White Band\n* [[Molly Meldrum|Ian \"Molly\" Meldrum]] (b