{"title_page": "Protoplasm", "text_new": "'''Protoplasm'''  is the living part of a [[cell (biology)|cell]] that is surrounded by a [[plasma membrane]].\n\nIn some definitions, it is a general term for the [[cytoplasm]] (e.g., Mohl, 1846),<ref name=\"Cammack\">{{Citation |author1=Cammack, Richard |author2=Teresa Atwood |author3=Attwood, Teresa K. |author4=Campbell, Peter Scott |author5=Parish, Howard I. |author6=Smith, Tony |author7=Vella, Frank |author8=Stirling, John |title=Oxford dictionary of biochemistry and molecular biology |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford [Oxfordshire] |year=2006 |isbn=978-0-19-852917-0}}</ref> but for others, it also includes the [[nucleoplasm]] (e.g., Strasburger, 1882). For Sharp (1921), \"According to the older usage the extra-nuclear portion of the [[protoplast]] [''the entire cell, excluding the cell wall''] was called \"protoplasm,\" but the nucleus also is composed of protoplasm, or living substance in its broader sense. The current consensus is to avoid this ambiguity by employing [[Eduard Strasburger|Strasburger]]'s [''(1882)''] terms cytoplasm [''coined by [[Albert von K\u00f6lliker|K\u00f6lliker]] (1863), originally as synonym for protoplasm''] and [[nucleoplasm]] ([''term coined by [[Edouard Van Beneden|van Beneden]] (1875), or''] karyoplasm, [''used by''] [[Walther Flemming|Flemming]] [''(1878)''])\".<ref>Sharp, L. W. (1921). ''[https://archive.org/details/introductiontocy032473mbp Introduction To Cytology]''. New York: McGraw Hill, p. 25.</ref><ref>Strasburger, E. (1882). Ueber den Theilungsvorgang der Zellkerne und das Verh\u00e4ltnis der Kernteilung zur Zellteilung. ''Arch Mikr Anat'', 21: 476-590, [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/49525#page/536/mode/1up BHL].</ref><ref>Beneden, E. van (1875). La maturation de l'oeuf, la f\u00e9condation et les premi\u00e8res de d\u00e9veloppement embryonnaire des Mammiferes d'apr\u00e8s les recherches faites chez le lapin. ''Bull. Acad. Bel. Cl. Sci.'' 40, 2 s\u00e8r.: 686-736, [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/28486#page/714/mode/1up BHL].</ref><ref>Flemming, W. (1878). Beitr\u00e4ge zur Kenntniss der Zelle und ihrer Lebenserscheinungen. ''Arch. f. mikr. Anat.'', 16: 302-436, p. 360, [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/49519#page/370/mode/1up BHL].</ref><ref>Battaglia, E. (2009). [http://www.caryologia.unifi.it/past_volumes/62_4supplement/62-4_supplement.pdf Caryoneme alternative to chromosome and a new caryological nomenclature]. ''Caryologia'', 62(4), 1.</ref> The cytoplasm definition of Strasburger excluded the [[plastid]]s (''Chromatoplasm'').\n\nLike the nucleus, whether to include the [[vacuole]] in the protoplasm concept is controversial.<ref>Parker, J. 1972. Protoplasmic resistance to water deficits, p. 125-176. In: Kozlowski, T. T. (ed.), ''Water deficits and plant growth''. Vol. III. Plant responses and control of water balance. Academic Press, New York, p. 144, [https://books.google.com/books?id=gOEr2alLRUYC].</ref>\n\n==Terminology==\nBesides \"protoplasm\", many are gay and orange other related terms and distinctions were used for the cell contents over time .These were as follows:<ref>Sharp (1921), p. 11, 32-34.</ref><ref name=battaglia>Battaglia, E. (1985). [https://books.google.com/books?id=gantAAAAMAAJ&q=Annali+di+botanica,+Volumes+43-45&dq=Annali+di+botanica,+Volumes+43-45&hl=en&sa=X&ei=pFPqU6GaHbO-sQTHrYCgCA&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAA Meiosis and mitosis: a terminological criticism]. ''Annali di Botanica'' (Rome) 43: 101\u2013140. (Table 3, \"-plasma derivatives\", p. 118).</ref> \n* ''[[Urschleim]]'' ([[Lorenz Oken|Oken]], 1802, 1809),<ref>''Grundriss der Naturphilosophie''.</ref><ref>''Lehrbuch der Naturphilosophie''.</ref>\n* ''Protoplasma'' (Purkinje, 1840, von Mohl, 1846),<ref name=purkinje/><ref name=Mohl/>\n* ''Primordialschlauch'' (primordial utricle, von Mohl, 1846),<ref name=Mohl/>\n* ''[[Amoeba#Amoebae as organisms|sarcode]]'' ([[F\u00e9lix Dujardin|Dujardin]], 1835, 1841),<ref>Dujardin, F. 1835. Recherches sur les organisms inf\u00e9rieurs. ''Annales des Sciences Naturelles'' 4: 343\u2013377, [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org//item/47932#page/347/mode/1up].</ref><ref>Dujardin, F. (1841). ''Histoire Naturelle des Zoophytes Infusoires''. Paris: Librarie Encyclopedique de Roret. p. 26.</ref>\n* ''[[Cytoplasm]]a'' ([[Rudolf von K\u00f6lliker|K\u00f6lliker]], 1863),<ref>K\u00f6lliker, R. A. v. (1863). [https://books.google.com/books?id=5mtARc4NAi0C ''Handbuch der Gewebelehre des Menschen.''] 4. Auflage. Leipzig: Wilhelm Engelmann.</ref>\n* ''Hautschicht/K\u00f6rnerschicht'' ([[ectoplasm (cell biology)|ectoplasm]]/[[endoplasm]], Pringsheim, 1854; Hofmeister, 1867),<ref name=\"Wayne 2009, p. 134\">Wayne (2009), p. 134.</ref><ref>Vines, S. H. (1877). An account of Prof. Strasburger's observation on protoplasm. ''Quart. J. Micr. Sc.'', Lond., 1877, n. s., 17, pp. 124-132. [https://books.google.com/books?id=kYLzAAAAMAAJ link].</ref>\n* ''Grundsubstanz'' ([[ground substance]], [[Cienkowski]], 1863),<ref>Cienkowski, L. 1863. Zur Entwicklungsgeschichte der Myxomyceten. ''Jahrb. Wiss. Bot.'' 3: 325-337, [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/30570#page/341/mode/1up].</ref>\n* [[metaplasm]]/protoplasm (Hanstein, 1868),<ref name=\"Wayne 2009, p. 134\"/> \n* [[deutoplasm]]/protoplasm (van Beneden, 1870),<ref>Van Beneden, E. ''Recherches sur la composition et la signification de l'\u0153uf''. F. Hayez, Bruxelles, 1870 (Extrait du tome XXXIV des ''M\u00e9m. cour. des savants \u00e9trangers'', publi\u00e9s par l'Acad\u00e9mie royale des sciences, des lettres et des beaux-arts de Belgique). [https://books.google.com/books?id=IvYYAAAAYAAJ link].</ref>\n* bioplasm (Beale, 1872),<ref name=beale/>\n* paraplasm/protoplasm (Kupffer, 1875),<ref>Kupffer, K. W. 1875. Ueber Differenzierung des Protoplasmas an den Zellen tierischer Gewebe. ''Schriften des Naturwissenschaft, Vereins f\u00fcr Schleswig-Holstein'', 1 (3), 229-242, [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/43486#page/253/mode/1up link].</ref> \n* inter-filar substance theory (Velten, 1876)<ref>Velten, W. 1876. Die physikalische Beschaffenhoit des pflanzlichon Protoplasmas. ''Sitzber. Akad. Wiss. Wien, Math.-Nat. Kl.'', 73: I 131-151, [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/35550#page/155/mode/1up].</ref>\n* ''[[Hyaloplasm]]a'' (Pfeffer, 1877),<ref>Pfeffer, W. ''Osmotische Untersuchungen''. W. Engelmann, Leipzig. [https://books.google.com/books?id=XTEbAAAAYAAJ link].</ref> \n* ''[[Protoplast]]'' (Hanstein, 1880),<ref>Hanstein (1880), p. 45.</ref> \n* ''Enchylema/Hyaloplasma'' (Hanstein, 1880),<ref>Hanstein (1880), pp. 24, 39.</ref> \n* ''Kleink\u00f6rperchen'' or ''Mikrosomen'' (small bodies or [[microsomes]], Hanstein, 1882),<ref name=\"Wayne 2009, p. 134\"/>\n* paramitome (Flemming, 1882),<ref>Flemming, W. (1882). ''Zellsubstanz, Kern, und Zelltheilung''. Vogel, Leipzig, [https://archive.org/details/zellsubstanzker02flemgoog].</ref> \n* ''[[Idioplasm]]a'' (Nageli, 1884),<ref name=battaglia/> \n* ''Zwischensubstanz'' (inter-alveolar substance, [[Otto B\u00fctschli|B\u00fctschli]], 1892),<ref>B\u00fctschli, O. 1892. ''Untersuchungen \u00fcber mikroskopische Sch\u00e4ume und das Protoplasma''. Leipzig, [https://archive.org/details/untersuchungen00btuoft].</ref> \n* ''Grundplasma'' (ground plasma, Sch\u00fctt, 1895),<ref>Sch\u00fctt, F. (1895). Die Peridineen der Plankton Expedition. Ergebnisse der Plankton-Expedition des Humbold-Stiftung, Bd IV, p. 1\u201327, Lipsius & Tischer, Kiel. [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_TxQWAAAAYAAJ link].</ref>\n* ''[[ergastoplasm]]e'' (Garnier, 1897),<ref name=battaglia/>\n* phaneroplasm/cryptoplasm (Seifriz, 1931),<ref>Seifriz, W. (1931). The structure of protoplasm. ''Science'' 73, 648-649. [http://science.sciencemag.org/content/73/1902/648 link].</ref>\n* cytoplasmic matrix (Munson, 1899; ''zytoplasmatische Matrix'', Bergmann, 1956),<ref>Munson, J. P., 1899 The Ovarian Egg of Limulus. Athenaeum Press, Boston, Massachusetts</ref><ref>Bargmann, W. (1956). \u00dcber einige Probleme und Ergebnisse des elektronen-mikroskopischen Studiums der Zelle. ''Dtsch. med. Wschr.'' 81 (28): 1109-1125.</ref>\n* ''Protoplasma- oder Zelleinschl\u00fcsse'' (protoplasmic or cellular [[Cytoplasmic inclusion|inclusions]], Szymonowicz, 1901),<ref>Szymonowicz, L. (1901). ''Lehrbuch der Histologie und der mikroskopischen Anatomie.'' Stuber, W\u00fcrzburg. [https://books.google.com/books?id=nctyflUBQgAC link].</ref><ref>Szymonowicz, L. (1902). ''Textbook of histology and microscopic anatomy of the human body, including microscopic technique''. Philadelphia, Lea Bros. [https://archive.org/details/textbookofhistol00szymrich link].</ref>\n* kinoplasm/trophoplasm (Strasburger et at., 1912),<ref name=\"Wayne 2009, p. 134\"/>\n* [[cytosol]] (Lardy, 1965).<ref name=lardy/>\n\n==History==\nThe word \"protoplasm\" comes from the Greek ''protos'' for ''first'', and ''plasma'' for ''thing formed'', and was originally used in religious contexts.<ref>Wayne, R. 2009. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=t_biw80LgjwC Plant Cell Biology: From Astronomy to Zoology]''. Amsterdam: Elsevier/Academic Press, p. 133.</ref> It was used in 1839 by [[Jan Evangelista Purkyn\u011b|J. E. Purkinje]] for the material of the animal embryo.<ref name=purkinje>Purkinje J.E. 1840. [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/120979#page/85/mode/1up \u00dcber die Analogien in den Strukturelementen des thierischen und pflanzichen Organismus]. In: ''\u00dcbersicht der Arbeiten und Ver\u00e4nderungen der schlesischen Gesellschaft f\u00fcr vaterl\u00e4ndische Kultur'', Jahre 1839: 81.</ref><ref>Bynum, W. F., Browne, E. J. & Porter, R. (1981). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=Ian_AwAAQBAJ Dictionary of the history of science]''. Princeton University Press.</ref> Later, in 1846 [[Hugo von Mohl]] redefined the term (also named as ''Primordialschlauch'', \"primordial utricle\") to refer to the \"tough, slimy, granular, semi-fluid\" substance within plant cells, to distinguish this from the [[cell wall]] and the [[cell sap]] (''Zellsaft'') within the [[vacuole]].<ref name=Mohl>von Mohl, H. 1846. [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/101480#page/47/mode/1up Ueber die Saftbewegung im Inneren der Zellen]. ''Bot. Ztg.'' 4: 73-78, 89-94.</ref><ref>Larson, P. R. (1994). ''The Vascular Cambium: Development and Structure.'' Springer-Verlag: New York and Berlin, p. 30-31, [https://books.google.com/books?id=7mLwCAAAQBAJ].</ref><ref>Evert, R. F. 2006. ''Esau's Plant Anatomy: Meristems, Cells, and Tissues of the Plant Body: Their Structure, Function, and Development''. 3rd.ed. John Wiley & Sons, Inc: Hoboken, New.Jersey, p. 16, [https://books.google.com/books?id=0DhEBA5xgbkC].</ref> [[Thomas Henry Huxley|Thomas Huxley]] (1869) later referred to it as the \"physical basis of life\" and considered that the property of life resulted from the distribution of molecules within this substance.<ref>Huxley, T. H. 1869. ''[https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/bibliography/24707#/summary The Physical Basis of Life]''. New Haven, Conn., The College Courant.</ref> The protoplasm became an \"[[Experimental system|epistemic thing]]\".<ref>Brain, R.M. \"Protoplasmania: Huxley, Haeckel, and the Vibratory Organism in Fin de Si\u00e8cle Visual Cultures\", in ''The Art of Evolution: Darwin, Darwinisms, and Visual Cultures'', F. Brauer and Larson, B. University Presses of New England, 2009, pp. 92-123, [https://books.google.com/books?id=kZisTVt0GJQC].</ref> Its composition, however, was mysterious and there was much controversy over what sort of substance it was.<ref name=\"Harvey2004\">{{citation | author = Harvey, E. N. | year = 1938 | title = Some Physical Properties of Protoplasm | journal = Journal of Applied Physics | volume = 9 | pages = 68\u201380 | doi = 10.1063/1.1710397 | url = http://link.aip.org/link/?JAPIAU/9/68/1 | issue = 2 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://archive.today/20130112050146/http://link.aip.org/link/?JAPIAU/9/68/1 | archivedate = 2013-01-12 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1872, [[Lionel Smith Beale|Beale]] created the [[vitalist]] term \"bioplasm\", to contrast with the [[materialism]] of Huxley.<ref name=beale>Beale, L. S. (1872). ''[https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/bibliography/31392#/summary Bioplasm]''. London: J. & A. Churchill.</ref><ref>Bynum et al. (1981), p. 344.</ref> In 1880, term [[protoplast]] was proposed by [[Johannes von Hanstein|Hanstein]] (1880) for the entire cell, excluding the cell wall,<ref>Hanstein, J. (1880). ''[https://archive.org/details/DasProtoplasma Das Protoplasma]''. Heidelberg.</ref><ref>Sharp (1921), p. 24.</ref> and some authors like [[Julius von Sachs]] (1882) preferred that name instead of cell.<ref>Wayne (2009), p. 15.</ref>\n\nIn 1965, Lardy introduced the term \"[[cytosol]]\", later redefined to refer to the liquid inside cells.<ref name=lardy>Lardy, H. A. 1965. On the direction of pyridine nucleotide oxidation-reduction reactions in gluconeogenesis and lipogenesis. In: ''Control of energy metabolism'', edited by B. Chance, R. Estabrook, and J. R. Williamson. New York: Academic, 1965, p. 245, [https://books.google.com/books?id=MUueBQAAQBAJ].</ref>\n\nBy the time Huxley wrote, a long-standing debate was largely settled over the fundamental unit of life: was it the cell or was it protoplasm? By the late 1860s, the debate was largely settled in favor of protoplasm. The cell was a container for protoplasm, the fundamental and universal material substance of life. Huxley's principal contribution was to establish protoplasm as incompatible with a [[vitalism|vitalistic theory of life]].<ref name=\"Geison1969\">{{citation | author = Geison, Gerald| year = 1969 | title = The Protoplasmic Theory of Life and the Vitalist-Mechanist Debate| journal = Isis | volume = 60 | issue = 3 | pages = 272\u2013292 | doi=10.1086/350498| pmid = 4919832 }}</ref> Attempts to investigate the [[origin of life]] through the creation of synthetic \"protoplasm\" in the laboratory were not successful.<ref name=\"Lazcano2008\">{{citation |author1=Lazcano, A. |author2=Capone, S. |author3=Walde, P. |author4=Seebach, D. |author5=Ishikawa, T. |author6=Caputo, R. | year = 2008 | title = What Is Life? A Brief Historical Overview | journal = Chemistry & Biodiversity | volume = 5 | pages = 1\u201315 | doi = 10.1002/cbdv.200890001 | pmid = 18205130 | issue = 1}}</ref>\n\nThe idea that protoplasm of eukaryotes is simply divisible into a ground substance called \"cytoplasm\" and a structural body called the [[cell nucleus]] reflects the more primitive knowledge of cell structure that preceded the development of [[electron microscopy]], when it seemed that cytoplasm was a homogeneous fluid and the existence of most sub-cellular compartments, or how cells maintain their shape, was unknown.<ref name=\"Satir2004\">{{citation | author = Satir, P. | year = 2005 | title = Tour of organelles through the electron microscope: A reprinting of Keith R. Porter's classic Harvey Lecture with a new introduction | journal = The Anatomical Record Part A: Discoveries in Molecular, Cellular, and Evolutionary Biology | volume = 287A | pages = 1184\u20131204 | doi = 10.1002/ar.a.20222 | url = http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/cgi-bin/fulltext/112138393/HTMLSTART | archive-url = https://archive.today/20121216152059/http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/cgi-bin/fulltext/112138393/HTMLSTART | url-status = dead | archive-date = 2012-12-16 | pmid = 16265625 | issue = 2}}</ref> Today, it is known that the cell contents are structurally very complex and contain multiple [[organelle]]s, the cytoskeleton and [[biomolecular condensate]]s.\n\n==Description==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=August 2016}}\nProtoplasm is composed of a mixture of small molecules such as [[ion]]s, [[amino acid]]s, [[monosaccharide]]s and [[water]], and [[macromolecule]]s such as [[nucleic acid]]s, [[protein]]s, [[lipid]]s and [[polysaccharide]]s.<ref name=\"Guyton & Hall\">{{Citation|title=Textbook of Medical Physiology, Eleventh Edition|author1=Arthur C. Guyton |author2=John E. Hall |quote=Protoplasm is composed mainly of five basic substances: water, electrolytes, proteins, lipids and carbohydrates.|publisher=[[Saunders (publisher)|Saunders]]}}</ref> In [[eukaryote]]s the protoplasm surrounding the [[cell nucleus]] is known as the [[cytoplasm]] and that inside the nucleus as the [[nucleoplasm]]. In [[prokaryote]]s the material inside the plasma membrane is the bacterial cytoplasm, while in [[Gram-negative bacteria]] the region outside the plasma membrane but inside the outer membrane is the [[periplasmic space|periplasm]].\n\nProtoplasm was said to exist in two forms: a liquid-like sol state or a jelly-like gel state.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Molecular evolution|Chemical evolution]]\n* [[Membrane]]\n* [[Symplast]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Protoplasm|short=x}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cell biology]]\n", "text_old": "'''Protoplasm'''  is the living part of a [[cell (biology)|cell]] that is surrounded by a [[plasma membrane]].\n\nIn some definitions, it is a general term for the [[cytoplasm]] (e.g., Mohl, 1846),<ref name=\"Cammack\">{{Citation |author1=Cammack, Richard |author2=Teresa Atwood |author3=Attwood, Teresa K. |author4=Campbell, Peter Scott |author5=Parish, Howard I. |author6=Smith, Tony |author7=Vella, Frank |author8=Stirling, John |title=Oxford dictionary of biochemistry and molecular biology |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford [Oxfordshire] |year=2006 |isbn=978-0-19-852917-0}}</ref> but for others, it also includes the [[nucleoplasm]] (e.g., Strasburger, 1882). For Sharp (1921), \"According to the older usage the extra-nuclear portion of the [[protoplast]] [''the entire cell, excluding the cell wall''] was called \"protoplasm,\" but the nucleus also is composed of protoplasm, or living substance in its broader sense. The current consensus is to avoid this ambiguity by employing [[Eduard Strasburger|Strasburger]]'s [''(1882)''] terms cytoplasm [''coined by [[Albert von K\u00f6lliker|K\u00f6lliker]] (1863), originally as synonym for protoplasm''] and [[nucleoplasm]] ([''term coined by [[Edouard Van Beneden|van Beneden]] (1875), or''] karyoplasm, [''used by''] [[Walther Flemming|Flemming]] [''(1878)''])\".<ref>Sharp, L. W. (1921). ''[https://archive.org/details/introductiontocy032473mbp Introduction To Cytology]''. New York: McGraw Hill, p. 25.</ref><ref>Strasburger, E. (1882). Ueber den Theilungsvorgang der Zellkerne und das Verh\u00e4ltnis der Kernteilung zur Zellteilung. ''Arch Mikr Anat'', 21: 476-590, [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/49525#page/536/mode/1up BHL].</ref><ref>Beneden, E. van (1875). La maturation de l'oeuf, la f\u00e9condation et les premi\u00e8res de d\u00e9veloppement embryonnaire des Mammiferes d'apr\u00e8s les recherches faites chez le lapin. ''Bull. Acad. Bel. Cl. Sci.'' 40, 2 s\u00e8r.: 686-736, [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/28486#page/714/mode/1up BHL].</ref><ref>Flemming, W. (1878). Beitr\u00e4ge zur Kenntniss der Zelle und ihrer Lebenserscheinungen. ''Arch. f. mikr. Anat.'', 16: 302-436, p. 360, [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/49519#page/370/mode/1up BHL].</ref><ref>Battaglia, E. (2009). [http://www.caryologia.unifi.it/past_volumes/62_4supplement/62-4_supplement.pdf Caryoneme alternative to chromosome and a new caryological nomenclature]. ''Caryologia'', 62(4), 1.</ref> The cytoplasm definition of Strasburger excluded the [[plastid]]s (''Chromatoplasm'').\n\nLike the nucleus, whether to include the [[vacuole]] in the protoplasm concept is controversial.<ref>Parker, J. 1972. Protoplasmic resistance to water deficits, p. 125-176. In: Kozlowski, T. T. (ed.), ''Water deficits and plant growth''. Vol. III. Plant responses and control of water balance. Academic Press, New York, p. 144, [https://books.google.com/books?id=gOEr2alLRUYC].</ref>\n\n==Terminology==\nBesides \"protoplasm\", many other related terms and distinctions were used for the cell contents over time .These were as follows:<ref>Sharp (1921), p. 11, 32-34.</ref><ref name=battaglia>Battaglia, E. (1985). [https://books.google.com/books?id=gantAAAAMAAJ&q=Annali+di+botanica,+Volumes+43-45&dq=Annali+di+botanica,+Volumes+43-45&hl=en&sa=X&ei=pFPqU6GaHbO-sQTHrYCgCA&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAA Meiosis and mitosis: a terminological criticism]. ''Annali di Botanica'' (Rome) 43: 101\u2013140. (Table 3, \"-plasma derivatives\", p. 118).</ref> \n* ''[[Urschleim]]'' ([[Lorenz Oken|Oken]], 1802, 1809),<ref>''Grundriss der Naturphilosophie''.</ref><ref>''Lehrbuch der Naturphilosophie''.</ref>\n* ''Protoplasma'' (Purkinje, 1840, von Mohl, 1846),<ref name=purkinje/><ref name=Mohl/>\n* ''Primordialschlauch'' (primordial utricle, von Mohl, 1846),<ref name=Mohl/>\n* ''[[Amoeba#Amoebae as organisms|sarcode]]'' ([[F\u00e9lix Dujardin|Dujardin]], 1835, 1841),<ref>Dujardin, F. 1835. Recherches sur les organisms inf\u00e9rieurs. ''Annales des Sciences Naturelles'' 4: 343\u2013377, [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org//item/47932#page/347/mode/1up].</ref><ref>Dujardin, F. (1841). ''Histoire Naturelle des Zoophytes Infusoires''. Paris: Librarie Encyclopedique de Roret. p. 26.</ref>\n* ''[[Cytoplasm]]a'' ([[Rudolf von K\u00f6lliker|K\u00f6lliker]], 1863),<ref>K\u00f6lliker, R. A. v. (1863). [https://books.google.com/books?id=5mtARc4NAi0C ''Handbuch der Gewebelehre des Menschen.''] 4. Auflage. Leipzig: Wilhelm Engelmann.</ref>\n* ''Hautschicht/K\u00f6rnerschicht'' ([[ectoplasm (cell biology)|ectoplasm]]/[[endoplasm]], Pringsheim, 1854; Hofmeister, 1867),<ref name=\"Wayne 2009, p. 134\">Wayne (2009), p. 134.</ref><ref>Vines, S. H. (1877). An account of Prof. Strasburger's observation on protoplasm. ''Quart. J. Micr. Sc.'', Lond., 1877, n. s., 17, pp. 124-132. [https://books.google.com/books?id=kYLzAAAAMAAJ link].</ref>\n* ''Grundsubstanz'' ([[ground substance]], [[Cienkowski]], 1863),<ref>Cienkowski, L. 1863. Zur Entwicklungsgeschichte der Myxomyceten. ''Jahrb. Wiss. Bot.'' 3: 325-337, [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/30570#page/341/mode/1up].</ref>\n* [[metaplasm]]/protoplasm (Hanstein, 1868),<ref name=\"Wayne 2009, p. 134\"/> \n* [[deutoplasm]]/protoplasm (van Beneden, 1870),<ref>Van Beneden, E. ''Recherches sur la composition et la signification de l'\u0153uf''. F. Hayez, Bruxelles, 1870 (Extrait du tome XXXIV des ''M\u00e9m. cour. des savants \u00e9trangers'', publi\u00e9s par l'Acad\u00e9mie royale des sciences, des lettres et des beaux-arts de Belgique). [https://books.google.com/books?id=IvYYAAAAYAAJ link].</ref>\n* bioplasm (Beale, 1872),<ref name=beale/>\n* paraplasm/protoplasm (Kupffer, 1875),<ref>Kupffer, K. W. 1875. Ueber Differenzierung des Protoplasmas an den Zellen tierischer Gewebe. ''Schriften des Naturwissenschaft, Vereins f\u00fcr Schleswig-Holstein'', 1 (3), 229-242, [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/43486#page/253/mode/1up link].</ref> \n* inter-filar substance theory (Velten, 1876)<ref>Velten, W. 1876. Die physikalische Beschaffenhoit des pflanzlichon Protoplasmas. ''Sitzber. Akad. Wiss. Wien, Math.-Nat. Kl.'', 73: I 131-151, [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/35550#page/155/mode/1up].</ref>\n* ''[[Hyaloplasm]]a'' (Pfeffer, 1877),<ref>Pfeffer, W. ''Osmotische Untersuchungen''. W. Engelmann, Leipzig. [https://books.google.com/books?id=XTEbAAAAYAAJ link].</ref> \n* ''[[Protoplast]]'' (Hanstein, 1880),<ref>Hanstein (1880), p. 45.</ref> \n* ''Enchylema/Hyaloplasma'' (Hanstein, 1880),<ref>Hanstein (1880), pp. 24, 39.</ref> \n* ''Kleink\u00f6rperchen'' or ''Mikrosomen'' (small bodies or [[microsomes]], Hanstein, 1882),<ref name=\"Wayne 2009, p. 134\"/>\n* paramitome (Flemming, 1882),<ref>Flemming, W. (1882). ''Zellsubstanz, Kern, und Zelltheilung''. Vogel, Leipzig, [https://archive.org/details/zellsubstanzker02flemgoog].</ref> \n* ''[[Idioplasm]]a'' (Nageli, 1884),<ref name=battaglia/> \n* ''Zwischensubstanz'' (inter-alveolar substance, [[Otto B\u00fctschli|B\u00fctschli]], 1892),<ref>B\u00fctschli, O. 1892. ''Untersuchungen \u00fcber mikroskopische Sch\u00e4ume und das Protoplasma''. Leipzig, [https://archive.org/details/untersuchungen00btuoft].</ref> \n* ''Grundplasma'' (ground plasma, Sch\u00fctt, 1895),<ref>Sch\u00fctt, F. (1895). Die Peridineen der Plankton Expedition. Ergebnisse der Plankton-Expedition des Humbold-Stiftung, Bd IV, p. 1\u201327, Lipsius & Tischer, Kiel. [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_TxQWAAAAYAAJ link].</ref>\n* ''[[ergastoplasm]]e'' (Garnier, 1897),<ref name=battaglia/>\n* phaneroplasm/cryptoplasm (Seifriz, 1931),<ref>Seifriz, W. (1931). The structure of protoplasm. ''Science'' 73, 648-649. [http://science.sciencemag.org/content/73/1902/648 link].</ref>\n* cytoplasmic matrix (Munson, 1899; ''zytoplasmatische Matrix'', Bergmann, 1956),<ref>Munson, J. P., 1899 The Ovarian Egg of Limulus. Athenaeum Press, Boston, Massachusetts</ref><ref>Bargmann, W. (1956). \u00dcber einige Probleme und Ergebnisse des elektronen-mikroskopischen Studiums der Zelle. ''Dtsch. med. Wschr.'' 81 (28): 1109-1125.</ref>\n* ''Protoplasma- oder Zelleinschl\u00fcsse'' (protoplasmic or cellular [[Cytoplasmic inclusion|inclusions]], Szymonowicz, 1901),<ref>Szymonowicz, L. (1901). ''Lehrbuch der Histologie und der mikroskopischen Anatomie.'' Stuber, W\u00fcrzburg. [https://books.google.com/books?id=nctyflUBQgAC link].</ref><ref>Szymonowicz, L. (1902). ''Textbook of histology and microscopic anatomy of the human body, including microscopic technique''. Philadelphia, Lea Bros. [https://archive.org/details/textbookofhistol00szymrich link].</ref>\n* kinoplasm/trophoplasm (Strasburger et at., 1912),<ref name=\"Wayne 2009, p. 134\"/>\n* [[cytosol]] (Lardy, 1965).<ref name=lardy/>\n\n==History==\nThe word \"protoplasm\" comes from the Greek ''protos'' for ''first'', and ''plasma'' for ''thing formed'', and was originally used in religious contexts.<ref>Wayne, R. 2009. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=t_biw80LgjwC Plant Cell Biology: From Astronomy to Zoology]''. Amsterdam: Elsevier/Academic Press, p. 133.</ref> It was used in 1839 by [[Jan Evangelista Purkyn\u011b|J. E. Purkinje]] for the material of the animal embryo.<ref name=purkinje>Purkinje J.E. 1840. [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/120979#page/85/mode/1up \u00dcber die Analogien in den Strukturelementen des thierischen und pflanzichen Organismus]. In: ''\u00dcbersicht der Arbeiten und Ver\u00e4nderungen der schlesischen Gesellschaft f\u00fcr vaterl\u00e4ndische Kultur'', Jahre 1839: 81.</ref><ref>Bynum, W. F., Browne, E. J. & Porter, R. (1981). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=Ian_AwAAQBAJ Dictionary of the history of science]''. Princeton University Press.</ref> Later, in 1846 [[Hugo von Mohl]] redefined the term (also named as ''Primordialschlauch'', \"primordial utricle\") to refer to the \"tough, slimy, granular, semi-fluid\" substance within plant cells, to distinguish this from the [[cell wall]] and the [[cell sap]] (''Zellsaft'') within the [[vacuole]].<ref name=Mohl>von Mohl, H. 1846. [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/101480#page/47/mode/1up Ueber die Saftbewegung im Inneren der Zellen]. ''Bot. Ztg.'' 4: 73-78, 89-94.</ref><ref>Larson, P. R. (1994). ''The Vascular Cambium: Development and Structure.'' Springer-Verlag: New York and Berlin, p. 30-31, [https://books.google.com/books?id=7mLwCAAAQBAJ].</ref><ref>Evert, R. F. 2006. ''Esau's Plant Anatomy: Meristems, Cells, and Tissues of the Plant Body: Their Structure, Function, and Development''. 3rd.ed. John Wiley & Sons, Inc: Hoboken, New.Jersey, p. 16, [https://books.google.com/books?id=0DhEBA5xgbkC].</ref> [[Thomas Henry Huxley|Thomas Huxley]] (1869) later referred to it as the \"physical basis of life\" and considered that the property of life resulted from the distribution of molecules within this substance.<ref>Huxley, T. H. 1869. ''[https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/bibliography/24707#/summary The Physical Basis of Life]''. New Haven, Conn., The College Courant.</ref> The protoplasm became an \"[[Experimental system|epistemic thing]]\".<ref>Brain, R.M. \"Protoplasmania: Huxley, Haeckel, and the Vibratory Organism in Fin de Si\u00e8cle Visual Cultures\", in ''The Art of Evolution: Darwin, Darwinisms, and Visual Cultures'', F. Brauer and Larson, B. University Presses of New England, 2009, pp. 92-123, [https://books.google.com/books?id=kZisTVt0GJQC].</ref> Its composition, however, was mysterious and there was much controversy over what sort of substance it was.<ref name=\"Harvey2004\">{{citation | author = Harvey, E. N. | year = 1938 | title = Some Physical Properties of Protoplasm | journal = Journal of Applied Physics | volume = 9 | pages = 68\u201380 | doi = 10.1063/1.1710397 | url = http://link.aip.org/link/?JAPIAU/9/68/1 | issue = 2 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://archive.today/20130112050146/http://link.aip.org/link/?JAPIAU/9/68/1 | archivedate = 2013-01-12 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1872, [[Lionel Smith Beale|Beale]] created the [[vitalist]] term \"bioplasm\", to contrast with the [[materialism]] of Huxley.<ref name=beale>Beale, L. S. (1872). ''[https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/bibliography/31392#/summary Bioplasm]''. London: J. & A. Churchill.</ref><ref>Bynum et al. (1981), p. 344.</ref> In 1880, term [[protoplast]] was proposed by [[Johannes von Hanstein|Hanstein]] (1880) for the entire cell, excluding the cell wall,<ref>Hanstein, J. (1880). ''[https://archive.org/details/DasProtoplasma Das Protoplasma]''. Heidelberg.</ref><ref>Sharp (1921), p. 24.</ref> and some authors like [[Julius von Sachs]] (1882) preferred that name instead of cell.<ref>Wayne (2009), p. 15.</ref>\n\nIn 1965, Lardy introduced the term \"[[cytosol]]\", later redefined to refer to the liquid inside cells.<ref name=lardy>Lardy, H. A. 1965. On the direction of pyridine nucleotide oxidation-reduction reactions in gluconeogenesis and lipogenesis. In: ''Control of energy metabolism'', edited by B. Chance, R. Estabrook, and J. R. Williamson. New York: Academic, 1965, p. 245, [https://books.google.com/books?id=MUueBQAAQBAJ].</ref>\n\nBy the time Huxley wrote, a long-standing debate was largely settled over the fundamental unit of life: was it the cell or was it protoplasm? By the late 1860s, the debate was largely settled in favor of protoplasm. The cell was a container for protoplasm, the fundamental and universal material substance of life. Huxley's principal contribution was to establish protoplasm as incompatible with a [[vitalism|vitalistic theory of life]].<ref name=\"Geison1969\">{{citation | author = Geison, Gerald| year = 1969 | title = The Protoplasmic Theory of Life and the Vitalist-Mechanist Debate| journal = Isis | volume = 60 | issue = 3 | pages = 272\u2013292 | doi=10.1086/350498| pmid = 4919832 }}</ref> Attempts to investigate the [[origin of life]] through the creation of synthetic \"protoplasm\" in the laboratory were not successful.<ref name=\"Lazcano2008\">{{citation |author1=Lazcano, A. |author2=Capone, S. |author3=Walde, P. |author4=Seebach, D. |author5=Ishikawa, T. |author6=Caputo, R. | year = 2008 | title = What Is Life? A Brief Historical Overview | journal = Chemistry & Biodiversity | volume = 5 | pages = 1\u201315 | doi = 10.1002/cbdv.200890001 | pmid = 18205130 | issue = 1}}</ref>\n\nThe idea that protoplasm of eukaryotes is simply divisible into a ground substance called \"cytoplasm\" and a structural body called the [[cell nucleus]] reflects the more primitive knowledge of cell structure that preceded the development of [[electron microscopy]], when it seemed that cytoplasm was a homogeneous fluid and the existence of most sub-cellular compartments, or how cells maintain their shape, was unknown.<ref name=\"Satir2004\">{{citation | author = Satir, P. | year = 2005 | title = Tour of organelles through the electron microscope: A reprinting of Keith R. Porter's classic Harvey Lecture with a new introduction | journal = The Anatomical Record Part A: Discoveries in Molecular, Cellular, and Evolutionary Biology | volume = 287A | pages = 1184\u20131204 | doi = 10.1002/ar.a.20222 | url = http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/cgi-bin/fulltext/112138393/HTMLSTART | archive-url = https://archive.today/20121216152059/http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/cgi-bin/fulltext/112138393/HTMLSTART | url-status = dead | archive-date = 2012-12-16 | pmid = 16265625 | issue = 2}}</ref> Today, it is known that the cell contents are structurally very complex and contain multiple [[organelle]]s, the cytoskeleton and [[biomolecular condensate]]s.\n\n==Description==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=August 2016}}\nProtoplasm is composed of a mixture of small molecules such as [[ion]]s, [[amino acid]]s, [[monosaccharide]]s and [[water]], and [[macromolecule]]s such as [[nucleic acid]]s, [[protein]]s, [[lipid]]s and [[polysaccharide]]s.<ref name=\"Guyton & Hall\">{{Citation|title=Textbook of Medical Physiology, Eleventh Edition|author1=Arthur C. Guyton |author2=John E. Hall |quote=Protoplasm is composed mainly of five basic substances: water, electrolytes, proteins, lipids and carbohydrates.|publisher=[[Saunders (publisher)|Saunders]]}}</ref> In [[eukaryote]]s the protoplasm surrounding the [[cell nucleus]] is known as the [[cytoplasm]] and that inside the nucleus as the [[nucleoplasm]]. In [[prokaryote]]s the material inside the plasma membrane is the bacterial cytoplasm, while in [[Gram-negative bacteria]] the region outside the plasma membrane but inside the outer membrane is the [[periplasmic space|periplasm]].\n\nProtoplasm was said to exist in two forms: a liquid-like sol state or a jelly-like gel state.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Molecular evolution|Chemical evolution]]\n* [[Membrane]]\n* [[Symplast]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Protoplasm|short=x}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cell biology]]\n", "name_user": "165.255.93.249", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eTerminology)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protoplasm"}
{"title_page": "Paul Lotman", "text_new": "{{short description|American volleyball player}}\n{{Infobox volleyball biography\n| name           = Paul Lotman\n| image          = Paul Lotman 2014 01.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| caption        =\n| fullname       = Paul Michael Lotman\n| nickname       =\n| nationality    = {{flagicon|USA}} [[United States|American]]\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1985|11|3|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Lakewood, California|Lakewood, CA]], [[United States]]\n| hometown       =\n| height         = {{height|m=2.00|precision=0}}\n| weight         = {{convert|102|kg|lb|abbr=on}}\n| spike          = {{convert|336|cm|abbr=on}}\n| block          = {{convert|312|cm|abbr=on}}\n| college        = [[California State University, Long Beach|Long Beach State University]]\n| position       = Outside hitter\n| currentclub    = {{flagicon|IND}} [[Calicut Heroes]] \n| currentnumber  = 7\n| years          =2004\u20132008<br>2008<br>2008\u20132009<br>2009\u20132010<br>2010\u20132011<br>2011\u20132015<br>2015\u20132016<br>2017\u20132018<br>2018\u2013\n| teams          = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Long Beach State 49ers men's volleyball|Long Beach State 49ers]]<br> {{flagicon|PUR}} [[Plataneros de Corozal]]<br> {{flagicon|GRC}} [[PAOK Thessaloniki V.C.|PAOK Thessaloniki]]<br> {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Stade Poitevin Poitiers]]<br> {{flagicon|ITA}} [[BluVolley Verona]]<br> {{flagicon|POL}} [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]<br> {{flagicon|GER}} [[Berlin Recycling Volleys]]<br> {{flagicon|IDN}} [[Jakarta BNI Taplus]]<br> {{flagicon|IND}} [[Calicut Heroes]]\n| nationalyears  = 2008\u2013\n| nationalteam   = {{vb|USA}}\n| medaltemplates-title = Medal record\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport | Men\u2019s [[volleyball]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{USA}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[FIVB Volleyball Men's World Cup|World Cup]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2015 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Cup|2015 Japan]] | }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[FIVB World League|World League]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2014 FIVB Volleyball World League|2014 Florence]] | }}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2015 FIVB Volleyball World League|2015 Rio de Janeiro]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Men's Pan-American Volleyball Cup|Pan American Cup]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2008 Men's Pan-American Volleyball Cup|2008 Winnipeg]] | }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[NORCECA Men's Volleyball Championship|NORCECA Championship]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2013 Men's NORCECA Volleyball Championship|2013 Canada]] | }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[2011 Men's NORCECA Volleyball Championship|2011 Puerto Rico]] | }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[2009 Men's NORCECA Volleyball Championship|2009 Puerto Rico]] | }}\n}}\n\n'''Paul Michael Lotman''' (born 3 November 1985) is an [[United States|American]] [[volleyball player]], a member of the [[United States men's national volleyball team]] and [[India]]n club [[Calicut Heroes]], a participant of the [[Olympic Games]] [[2012 Summer Olympics|London 2012]], [[2013 Men's NORCECA Volleyball Championship|NORCECA Champion 2013]], gold medalist of the [[2008 Men's Pan-American Volleyball Cup|2008 Pan American Cup]], [[2014 FIVB Volleyball World League|2014 World League]] and [[2015 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Cup|2015 World Cup]], three\u2013time [[PlusLiga|Polish Champion]] ([[2011\u201312 PlusLiga|2012]], [[2012\u201313 PlusLiga|2013]], [[2014\u201315 PlusLiga|2015]]), [[Deutsche Volleyball-Bundesliga|German Champion]] (2016).\n\n==Personal life==\nLotman was born in [[Lakewood, California]]. His parents are Kathleen and Albert Lotman (his father died in 2011). He has two older brothers, Mark and Steven, and an older sister Shelley. He attended Los Alamitos High School (1999\u20132003). He graduated from [[California State University, Long Beach]] (better known as Long Beach State) in 2008 with a degree in sociology. On August 2011 he married Jasmine.<ref>[http://www.volleywood.net/usav-volleyball-news/lotmans-wedding-pics/ ''Lotman\u2019s Wedding Pics''] \u2013 volleywood.net \u2013 2011-08-23</ref> On December 20, 2016 his wife gave birth to their son Leif Albert Lotman.\n\n[[File:Paul Lotman.jpg|thumb|Lotman before match Piacenza \u2013 Verona on January 27, 2011.]]\n\n==Career==\n\n===Clubs===\nIn 2011 he joined the Polish club [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]].<ref>[http://volley24.pl/index.php/rozgrywki-mezczyzn/plusliga/14922-paul-lotman-kolejnym-przyjmujcym-w-rzeszowie ''Paul Lotman kolejnym przyjmuj\u0105cym w Rzeszowie''] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20140404162513/http://volley24.pl/index.php/rozgrywki-mezczyzn/plusliga/14922-paul-lotman-kolejnym-przyjmujcym-w-rzeszowie |date=April 4, 2014 }} \u2013 volley24.pl \u2013 2011-05-18</ref> With the club from [[Rzesz\u00f3w]] he won three titles of [[PlusLiga|Polish Champion]] ([[2011\u201312 PlusLiga|2012]], [[2012\u201313 PlusLiga|2013]], [[2014\u201315 PlusLiga|2015]]), Polish SuperCup and the silver medal of [[2011\u201312 Men's CEV Cup|CEV Cup]] 2012. On March 29, 2015 [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]], including Lotman, achieved silver medal of the [[2014\u201315 CEV Champions League]].<ref>[http://www.cev.eu/Competition-Area/CompetitionNews.aspx?ID=736&NewsID=19956&TagType=0&TagContent=0&NewsType=0&Paging=0&Sd=1/1/1900&Ed=1/1/1900 ''Three is the magic number for Russian armada from Tatarstan!''] \u2013 cev.eu \u2013 2015-03-29</ref> He left [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w|Asseco Resovia]] in May 2015. In June 2015 he moved to German team [[Berlin Recycling Volleys]].<ref>[http://eurosport.onet.pl/siatkowka/plus-liga/paul-lotman-siatkarzem-berlin-recycling-volleys/e7tcyl ''Paul Lotman siatkarzem Berlin Recycling Volleys''] \u2013 onet.pl \u2013 2015-06-18</ref> In 2017 he moved to Indonesian volleyball club [[Jakarta BNI Taplus]] for 2017/2018 season.\n\n===National team===\nLotman made his [[Olympic games|Olympic]] debut with the [[United States men's national volleyball team|U.S. national team]] in [[2012 Olympics]] in London.\n\n===Coaching===\nIn 2019, Lotman began working as a volunteer assistant coach with the [[UC San Diego]] Tritons men's volleyball team.\n\n==Sporting achievements==\n* '''[[CEV Champions League]]'''\n** [[File:Silver medal europe.svg|16px]] [[2014\u201315 CEV Champions League|2014/2015]] \u2013 with [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n* '''[[CEV Cup]]'''\n** [[File:Simple silver cup.svg|16px]] [[2011\u201312 Men's CEV Cup|2011/2012]] \u2013 with [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n** [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] [[2015\u201316 Men's CEV Cup|2015/2016]] \u2013 with [[Berlin Recycling Volleys]]\n* '''National championships'''\n** '''2007/2008''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] Puerto Rican Championship, with [[Plataneros de Corozal]]\n** '''2011/2012''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2011\u201312 PlusLiga|Polish Championship]], with [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n** '''2012/2013''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2012\u201313 PlusLiga|Polish Championship]], with [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n** '''2013/2014''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] Polish SuperCup, with [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n** '''2013/2014''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2013\u201314 PlusLiga|Polish Championship]], with [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n** '''2014/2015''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2014\u201315 PlusLiga|Polish Championship]], with [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n** '''2015/2016''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] German Cup, with [[Berlin Recycling Volleys]]\n** '''2015/2016''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Deutsche Volleyball-Bundesliga|German Championship]], with [[Berlin Recycling Volleys]]\n** '''2018/2019''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Pro Volleyball League|Indian Championship]], with [[Calicut Heroes]]\n* '''National team'''\n** '''2008''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] [[2008 Men's Pan-American Volleyball Cup|Pan-American Cup]]\n** '''2009''' [[File:Silver medal northamerica.svg|16px]] [[2009 Men's NORCECA Volleyball Championship|NORCECA Championship]]\n** '''2011''' [[File:Silver medal northamerica.svg|16px]] [[2011 Men's NORCECA Volleyball Championship|NORCECA Championship]]\n** '''2013''' [[File:Gold medal northamerica.svg|16px]] [[2013 Men's NORCECA Volleyball Championship|NORCECA Championship]]\n** '''2014''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2014 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]]\n** '''2015''' [[File:Bronze medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2015 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]]\n** '''2015''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] [[2015 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Cup|FIVB World Cup]]\n\n===Individually===\n* '''2016:''' [[2015\u201316 Men's CEV Cup|CEV Cup]] \u2013 Most Valuable Player\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* {{USOPC profile|LO/Paul-Lotman}}\n* [https://www.plusliga.pl/players/id/419.html PlusLiga player profile]\n* [https://www.instagram.com/paullotman/ Instagram player profile]\n\n{{United States men's volleyball squad 2012 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Footer USA Volleyball 2012 Summer Olympics}}\n{{United States men volleyball team 2015 FIVB World Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lotman, Paul}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lakewood, California]]\n[[Category:American men's volleyball players]]\n[[Category:Olympic volleyball players of the United States]]\n[[Category:Volleyball players at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Polish Champions of men's volleyball]]\n[[Category:Long Beach State Beach men's volleyball players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in Poland]]\n[[Category:Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w players]]\n[[Category:PAOK V.C. players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American volleyball player}}\n{{Infobox volleyball biography\n| name           = Paul Lotman\n| image          = Paul Lotman 2014 01.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| caption        =\n| fullname       = Paul Michael Lotman\n| nickname       =\n| nationality    = {{flagicon|USA}} [[United States|American]]\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1985|11|