ball Championship|2013 Canada]] | }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[2011 Men's NORCECA Volleyball Championship|2011 Puerto Rico]] | }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[2009 Men's NORCECA Volleyball Championship|2009 Puerto Rico]] | }}\n}}\n\n'''Paul Michael Lotman''' (born 3 November 1985) is an [[United States|American]] [[volleyball player]], a member of the [[United States men's national volleyball team]] and [[India|Indian]] club [[Calicut Heroes]], a participant of the [[Olympic Games]] [[2012 Summer Olympics|London 2012]], [[2013 Men's NORCECA Volleyball Championship|NORCECA Champion 2013]], gold medalist of the [[2008 Men's Pan-American Volleyball Cup|2008 Pan American Cup]], [[2014 FIVB Volleyball World League|2014 World League]] and [[2015 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Cup|2015 World Cup]], three\u2013time [[PlusLiga|Polish Champion]] ([[2011\u201312 PlusLiga|2012]], [[2012\u201313 PlusLiga|2013]], [[2014\u201315 PlusLiga|2015]]), [[Deutsche Volleyball-Bundesliga|German Champion]] (2016).\n\n==Personal life==\nLotman was born in [[Lakewood, California]]. His parents are Kathleen and Albert Lotman (his father died in 2011). He has two older brothers, Mark and Steven, and an older sister Shelley. He attended Los Alamitos High School (1999\u20132003). He graduated from [[California State University, Long Beach]] (better known as Long Beach State) in 2008 with a degree in sociology. On August 2011 he married Jasmine.<ref>[http://www.volleywood.net/usav-volleyball-news/lotmans-wedding-pics/ ''Lotman\u2019s Wedding Pics''] \u2013 volleywood.net \u2013 2011-08-23</ref> On December 20, 2016 his wife gave birth to their son Leif Albert Lotman.\n\n[[File:Paul Lotman.jpg|thumb|Lotman before match Piacenza \u2013 Verona on January 27, 2011.]]\n\n==Career==\n\n===Clubs===\nIn 2011 he joined the Polish club [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]].<ref>[http://volley24.pl/index.php/rozgrywki-mezczyzn/plusliga/14922-paul-lotman-kolejnym-przyjmujcym-w-rzeszowie ''Paul Lotman kolejnym przyjmuj\u0105cym w Rzeszowie''] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20140404162513/http://volley24.pl/index.php/rozgrywki-mezczyzn/plusliga/14922-paul-lotman-kolejnym-przyjmujcym-w-rzeszowie |date=April 4, 2014 }} \u2013 volley24.pl \u2013 2011-05-18</ref> With the club from [[Rzesz\u00f3w]] he won three titles of [[PlusLiga|Polish Champion]] ([[2011\u201312 PlusLiga|2012]], [[2012\u201313 PlusLiga|2013]], [[2014\u201315 PlusLiga|2015]]), Polish SuperCup and the silver medal of [[2011\u201312 Men's CEV Cup|CEV Cup]] 2012. On March 29, 2015 [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]], including Lotman, achieved silver medal of the [[2014\u201315 CEV Champions League]].<ref>[http://www.cev.eu/Competition-Area/CompetitionNews.aspx?ID=736&NewsID=19956&TagType=0&TagContent=0&NewsType=0&Paging=0&Sd=1/1/1900&Ed=1/1/1900 ''Three is the magic number for Russian armada from Tatarstan!''] \u2013 cev.eu \u2013 2015-03-29</ref> He left [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w|Asseco Resovia]] in May 2015. In June 2015 he moved to German team [[Berlin Recycling Volleys]].<ref>[http://eurosport.onet.pl/siatkowka/plus-liga/paul-lotman-siatkarzem-berlin-recycling-volleys/e7tcyl ''Paul Lotman siatkarzem Berlin Recycling Volleys''] \u2013 onet.pl \u2013 2015-06-18</ref> In 2017 he moved to Indonesian volleyball club [[Jakarta BNI Taplus]] for 2017/2018 season.\n\n===National team===\nLotman made his [[Olympic games|Olympic]] debut with the [[United States men's national volleyball team|U.S. national team]] in [[2012 Olympics]] in London.\n\n===Coaching===\nIn 2019, Lotman began working as a volunteer assistant coach with the [[UC San Diego]] Tritons men's volleyball team.\n\n==Sporting achievements==\n* '''[[CEV Champions League]]'''\n** [[File:Silver medal europe.svg|16px]] [[2014\u201315 CEV Champions League|2014/2015]] \u2013 with [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n\n* '''[[CEV Cup]]'''\n** [[File:Simple silver cup.svg|16px]] [[2011\u201312 Men's CEV Cup|2011/2012]] \u2013 with [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n** [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] [[2015\u201316 Men's CEV Cup|2015/2016]] \u2013 with [[Berlin Recycling Volleys]]\n\n* '''National championships'''\n** '''2007/2008''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] Puerto Rican Championship, with [[Plataneros de Corozal]]\n** '''2011/2012''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2011\u201312 PlusLiga|Polish Championship]], with [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n** '''2012/2013''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2012\u201313 PlusLiga|Polish Championship]], with [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n** '''2013/2014''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] Polish SuperCup, with [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n** '''2013/2014''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2013\u201314 PlusLiga|Polish Championship]], with [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n** '''2014/2015''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2014\u201315 PlusLiga|Polish Championship]], with [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n** '''2015/2016''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] German Cup, with [[Berlin Recycling Volleys]]\n** '''2015/2016''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Deutsche Volleyball-Bundesliga|German Championship]], with [[Berlin Recycling Volleys]]\n** '''2018/2019''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Pro Volleyball League|Indian Championship]], with [[Calicut Heroes]]\n\n* '''National team'''\n** '''2008''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] [[2008 Men's Pan-American Volleyball Cup|Pan-American Cup]]\n** '''2009''' [[File:Silver medal northamerica.svg|16px]] [[2009 Men's NORCECA Volleyball Championship|NORCECA Championship]]\n** '''2011''' [[File:Silver medal northamerica.svg|16px]] [[2011 Men's NORCECA Volleyball Championship|NORCECA Championship]]\n** '''2013''' [[File:Gold medal northamerica.svg|16px]] [[2013 Men's NORCECA Volleyball Championship|NORCECA Championship]]\n** '''2014''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2014 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]]\n** '''2015''' [[File:Bronze medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2015 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]]\n** '''2015''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] [[2015 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Cup|FIVB World Cup]]\n\n===Individually===\n* '''2016:''' [[2015\u201316 Men's CEV Cup|CEV Cup]] \u2013 Most Valuable Player\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [http://www.teamusa.org/Athletes/LO/Paul-Lotman Team USA player profile]\n* [https://www.plusliga.pl/players/id/419.html PlusLiga player profile]\n* [https://www.instagram.com/paullotman/ Instagram player profile]\n\n{{United States men's volleyball squad 2012 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Footer USA Volleyball 2012 Summer Olympics}}\n{{United States men volleyball team 2015 FIVB World Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lotman, Paul}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lakewood, California]]\n[[Category:American men's volleyball players]]\n[[Category:Olympic volleyball players of the United States]]\n[[Category:Volleyball players at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Polish Champions of men's volleyball]]\n[[Category:Long Beach State Beach men's volleyball players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in Poland]]\n[[Category:Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w players]]\n[[Category:PAOK V.C. players]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "use template for USOPC link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Lotman"}
{"title_page": "Legendary (film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name = Legendary\n| image = Legendary poster.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Mel Damski]]\n| producer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Michael Pavone]]\n* David Calloway}}\n| writer = John Posey\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[John Cena]]\n* [[Patricia Clarkson]]\n* [[Danny Glover]]\n}}\n| music = [[Jim Johnston (composer)|James A. Johnston]]\n| cinematography = Kenneth Zunder\n| editing = Mitch Stanley\n| studio = [[WWE Studios]]\n| distributor = [[Samuel Goldwyn Films]]\n| released = {{Film date|2010|9|10}}\n| runtime = 107 minutes<ref>[http://www.fandango.com/legendary_135746/movieoverview Fandango] web site.</ref>\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| budget = $5 million\n| gross = $200,393<ref>{{mojo title|legendary|Legendary}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Legendary''''' is a 2010 American [[sports film|sports]] [[drama film]] directed by [[Mel Damski]]. The film stars [[Devon Graye]] as a [[Scholastic wrestling|high school wrestler]], in a cast that features [[John Cena]], [[Patricia Clarkson]], [[Danny Glover]], [[Madeleine Martin]], and [[Tyler Posey]]. The film was released on September 10, 2010.\n\n==Plot==\n{{expand section|date=January 2015}}\nAfter being bullied, book-smart (but not street-wise) teenager Cal Chetley ([[Devon Graye]]), joins his [[Oklahoma]] high school's [[Scholastic wrestling|wrestling]] team, seeing it also as a way to reunite with his estranged and wayward brother, Mike ([[John Cena]]). His mother, Sharon ([[Patricia Clarkson]]), is not initially supportive of Cal's decision, especially when she discovers that Mike is secretly coaching Cal after she gets a call from Mike Chetley's jail cell. She has been away and without contact of her older son, Mike, for over 10 years, but copes and watches yet another family male become legendary.\nThen Ashley discovers jujila is gay after she discovers her watching Momo and Sue hentai.\n==Cast==\n* [[John Cena]] as Mike Chetley\n* [[Patricia Clarkson]] as Sharon Chetley\n* [[Danny Glover]] as Harry \"Red\" Newman \n* [[Devon Graye]] as Cal Chetley\n* [[Madeleine Martin]] as Luli Stringfellow\n* [[Tyler Posey]] as Billy Barrow\n* [[John Posey (actor)|John Posey]] as Coach Stu Tennent\n* Teo Olivares as Donald Worthington\n* Chris Whetstone as Mac Chetley\n\n==Production==\n[[WWE Studios]] produced the film alongside [[Samuel Goldwyn Films]]. Filming took place at Bonnabel Magnet Academy High School in [[Kenner|Kenner, Louisiana]] in December 2009.<ref>[http://www.wrestlingnewsarena.com/2009/11/john-cena-to-begin-filming-new-movie-soon/ \"John Cena to Begin Filming New Movie Soon\"], WrestlingNewsArena.com</ref>\n\n==Music==\nAlthough no official soundtrack was released, the following songs appeared in the movie:\n\n* \"Blue Jeans\" performed by Glass Cow\n* \"Crash\" performed by Fit for Rivals\n* \"Dragonfly\" performed by Shaman\u2019s Harvest\n* \"Faith\" performed by James A. Johnston & Laci Williams\n* \"Flash Lightnin\u2019\" performed by Flash Lightnin\u2019\n* \"Hard Line\" performed by James A. Johnston\n* \"Hustle, Loyalty, Respect\" performed by [[John Cena]] and [[Freddie Foxxx]] (Also used in the trailer)\n* \"In the Morning\" performed by Taddy Porter\n* \"It\u2019s Your Last Shot\" performed by Politics & Assassins\n* \"Letters from the Sky\" performed by Civil Twilight\n* \"Liar\" performed by Glasgow\n* \"One Night\" performed by Golden State\n* \"Panis Angelicus\" composed by Cesar Franch\n* \"Railroad Queen\" performed by Taddy Porter\n* \"Take Back the Fear\" performed by [[Hail the Villain]]\n* \"The Dream\" composed & orchestrated by James A. Johnston with vocals by Jonathan Estabrook\n* \"Through Telescopes\" performed by Colour Academy (Also used in the trailer)\n* \"Undertow\" performed by Beta Wolf\t\n* \"We Must Start Again\" performed by Golden State\n\nThe orchestral score, written, and composed by James A Johnston, is available on iTunes.\n\n==Home media==\nThe film was released on [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] and [[DVD]] on September 28, 2010. The DVD is being sold exclusively at [[Wal-Mart|Walmart]] and the Blu-ray exclusively at [[Best Buy]].<ref>[http://www.yardbarker.com/wwe/articles/legendary_dvd_release_date_92810/3266630 Yard Baker] web site (Fox Sports).</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nCritics received the film poorly. On [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 19% based on 43 reviews, and an [[average rating]] of 4.8/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"Maudlin, predictable, and clich\u00e9d, ''Legendary'' pins its talented cast under a heavy layer of formulaic schmaltz.\"<ref>{{rotten-tomatoes|legendary}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 39 out of 100, based on 17 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{metacritic film|legendary}}</ref>\n\n''Legendary'' failed to make the top ten at the box office in its only weekend in [[wide release]], finishing with $200,393 in total.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.legendarythemovie.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|1563704|Legendary}}\n* {{AllRovi movie|517961|Legendary}}\n* {{mojo title|legendary|Legendary}}\n* {{Metacritic film|legendary|Legendary}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|legendary|Legendary}}\n\n{{Mel Damski}}\n{{WWE Studios}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Legendary}}\n[[Category:2010 films]]\n[[Category:2010s sports drama films]]\n[[Category:American sports drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New Orleans]]\n[[Category:Sport wrestling films]]\n[[Category:WWE Studios films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Mel Damski]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name = Legendary\n| image = Legendary poster.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Mel Damski]]\n| producer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Michael Pavone]]\n* David Calloway}}\n| writer = John Posey\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[John Cena]]\n* [[Patricia Clarkson]]\n* [[Danny Glover]]\n}}\n| music = [[Jim Johnston (composer)|James A. Johnston]]\n| cinematography = Kenneth Zunder\n| editing = Mitch Stanley\n| studio = [[WWE Studios]]\n| distributor = [[Samuel Goldwyn Films]]\n| released = {{Film date|2010|9|10}}\n| runtime = 107 minutes<ref>[http://www.fandango.com/legendary_135746/movieoverview Fandango] web site.</ref>\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| budget = $5 million\n| gross = $200,393<ref>{{mojo title|legendary|Legendary}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Legendary''''' is a 2010 American [[sports film|sports]] [[drama film]] directed by [[Mel Damski]]. The film stars [[Devon Graye]] as a [[Scholastic wrestling|high school wrestler]], in a cast that features [[John Cena]], [[Patricia Clarkson]], [[Danny Glover]], [[Madeleine Martin]], and [[Tyler Posey]]. The film was released on September 10, 2010.\n\n==Plot==\n{{expand section|date=January 2015}}\nAfter being bullied, book-smart (but not street-wise) teenager Cal Chetley ([[Devon Graye]]), joins his [[Oklahoma]] high school's [[Scholastic wrestling|wrestling]] team, seeing it also as a way to reunite with his estranged and wayward brother, Mike ([[John Cena]]). His mother, Sharon ([[Patricia Clarkson]]), is not initially supportive of Cal's decision, especially when she discovers that Mike is secretly coaching Cal after she gets a call from Mike Chetley's jail cell. She has been away and without contact of her older son, Mike, for over 10 years, but copes and watches yet another family male become legendary.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[John Cena]] as Mike Chetley\n* [[Patricia Clarkson]] as Sharon Chetley\n* [[Danny Glover]] as Harry \"Red\" Newman \n* [[Devon Graye]] as Cal Chetley\n* [[Madeleine Martin]] as Luli Stringfellow\n* [[Tyler Posey]] as Billy Barrow\n* [[John Posey (actor)|John Posey]] as Coach Stu Tennent\n* Teo Olivares as Donald Worthington\n* Chris Whetstone as Mac Chetley\n\n==Production==\n[[WWE Studios]] produced the film alongside [[Samuel Goldwyn Films]]. Filming took place at Bonnabel Magnet Academy High School in [[Kenner|Kenner, Louisiana]] in December 2009.<ref>[http://www.wrestlingnewsarena.com/2009/11/john-cena-to-begin-filming-new-movie-soon/ \"John Cena to Begin Filming New Movie Soon\"], WrestlingNewsArena.com</ref>\n\n==Music==\nAlthough no official soundtrack was released, the following songs appeared in the movie:\n\n* \"Blue Jeans\" performed by Glass Cow\n* \"Crash\" performed by Fit for Rivals\n* \"Dragonfly\" performed by Shaman\u2019s Harvest\n* \"Faith\" performed by James A. Johnston & Laci Williams\n* \"Flash Lightnin\u2019\" performed by Flash Lightnin\u2019\n* \"Hard Line\" performed by James A. Johnston\n* \"Hustle, Loyalty, Respect\" performed by [[John Cena]] and [[Freddie Foxxx]] (Also used in the trailer)\n* \"In the Morning\" performed by Taddy Porter\n* \"It\u2019s Your Last Shot\" performed by Politics & Assassins\n* \"Letters from the Sky\" performed by Civil Twilight\n* \"Liar\" performed by Glasgow\n* \"One Night\" performed by Golden State\n* \"Panis Angelicus\" composed by Cesar Franch\n* \"Railroad Queen\" performed by Taddy Porter\n* \"Take Back the Fear\" performed by [[Hail the Villain]]\n* \"The Dream\" composed & orchestrated by James A. Johnston with vocals by Jonathan Estabrook\n* \"Through Telescopes\" performed by Colour Academy (Also used in the trailer)\n* \"Undertow\" performed by Beta Wolf\t\n* \"We Must Start Again\" performed by Golden State\n\nThe orchestral score, written, and composed by James A Johnston, is available on iTunes.\n\n==Home media==\nThe film was released on [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] and [[DVD]] on September 28, 2010. The DVD is being sold exclusively at [[Wal-Mart|Walmart]] and the Blu-ray exclusively at [[Best Buy]].<ref>[http://www.yardbarker.com/wwe/articles/legendary_dvd_release_date_92810/3266630 Yard Baker] web site (Fox Sports).</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nCritics received the film poorly. On [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 19% based on 43 reviews, and an [[average rating]] of 4.8/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"Maudlin, predictable, and clich\u00e9d, ''Legendary'' pins its talented cast under a heavy layer of formulaic schmaltz.\"<ref>{{rotten-tomatoes|legendary}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 39 out of 100, based on 17 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{metacritic film|legendary}}</ref>\n\n''Legendary'' failed to make the top ten at the box office in its only weekend in [[wide release]], finishing with $200,393 in total.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.legendarythemovie.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|1563704|Legendary}}\n* {{AllRovi movie|517961|Legendary}}\n* {{mojo title|legendary|Legendary}}\n* {{Metacritic film|legendary|Legendary}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|legendary|Legendary}}\n\n{{Mel Damski}}\n{{WWE Studios}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Legendary}}\n[[Category:2010 films]]\n[[Category:2010s sports drama films]]\n[[Category:American sports drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New Orleans]]\n[[Category:Sport wrestling films]]\n[[Category:WWE Studios films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Mel Damski]]\n", "name_user": "41.223.117.75", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legendary_(film)"}
